, pp.&nbsp;175\u2013178:) \"The [[autograph (music)|autographs]] of [[Wilhelm Friedemann Bach]]\" |chapter-url=https://journals.qucosa.de/ejournals/bjb/article/view/1745 |editor1-last=Schulze |editor1-first=Hans-Joachim |editor2-last=Wolff |editor2-first=Christoph |display-editors= |title=Bach-Jahrbuch 2002 |trans-title=Bach Yearbook 2002 |url=https://journals.qucosa.de/ejournals/bjb/issue/view/163 |series=[[Bach-Jahrbuch]] |language=de |volume=88 |others=[[Neue Bachgesellschaft]] |location=Leipzig |publisher={{ill|Evangelische Verlagsanstalt|de}} |pages=165\u2013180 |doi=10.13141/bjb.v2002 |isbn=3-374-02031-3 |issn=0084-7682 |ref={{SfnRef|Gl\u00f6ckner et al.|2002}} }}\n* {{cite book |last1=Gl\u00f6ckner |first1=Andreas |author-link1=Andreas Gl\u00f6ckner |date=2009 |chapter=Ein weiterer Kantatenjahrgang Gottfried Heinrich St\u00f6lzels in Bachs Auff\u00fchrungsrepertoire? |trans-chapter=Is there another cantata cycle by Gottfried Heinrich St\u00f6lzel that belonged to Bach\u2019s performance repertoire? |chapter-url=https://journals.qucosa.de/ejournals/bjb/article/view/1861 |editor1-last=Wollny |editor1-first=Peter |editor1-link=Peter Wollny |title=Bach-Jahrbuch 2009 |trans-title=Bach Yearbook 2009 |url=https://journals.qucosa.de/ejournals/bjb/issue/view/170 |series=[[Bach-Jahrbuch]] |language=de |volume=95 |others=[[Neue Bachgesellschaft]] |location=Leipzig |publisher={{ill|Evangelische Verlagsanstalt|de}} |pages=95\u2013115 |doi=10.13141/bjb.v2009 |isbn=978-3-374-02749-1 |issn=0084-7682 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last1=Hegen |first1=Irene |date=2018 |chapter=Die markgr\u00e4fliche Hofkapelle zu Bayreuth (1661\u20131769) |trans-chapter= |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=X81-DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA1 |editor1-last=Leopold |editor1-first=Silke |editor1-link=Silke Leopold |editor2-last=Pelker |editor2-first=B\u00e4rbel |editor2-link= |title=S\u00fcddeutsche Hofkapellen im 18. Jahrhundert: Eine Bestandsaufnahme |trans-title= |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=X81-DwAAQBAJ |language=de |publisher=[[Books on Demand]] |pages=1\u201354 |isbn=9783946054788 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite journal |date=1890 |title=Ges\u00e4nge f\u00fcr eine Singstimme mit Pianoforte |trans-title=Songs for one singing voice and pianoforte |url=http://anno.onb.ac.at/cgi-content/anno-buch?apm=0&aid=1000001&bd=0001890&teil=0203&seite=00000340 |journal=Musikalisch-literarischer Monatsbericht |language=de |location=Leipzig |publisher=[[Friedrich Hofmeister Musikverlag|Friedrich Hofmeister]] |volume=[http://anno.onb.ac.at/cgi-content/anno-buch?apm=0&aid=1000001&bd=0001890&teil=0101&seite=00000001 62] |issue=[http://anno.onb.ac.at/cgi-content/anno-buch?apm=0&aid=1000001&bd=0001890&teil=0203&seite=00000305 8] |pages=340\u2013348 |ref={{harvid|Hofmeister|1890}} }}\n* {{BDh|4312|0|2018-11-20|Source|Klavierb\u00fcchlein f\u00fcr W. F. Bach (US-NHub Music Deposit)}}\n* {{cite journal |date=1754 |editor1-last=Mizler |editor1-first=Lorenz Christoph |editor1-link=Lorenz Christoph Mizler |title=VI. Denkmal dreyer verstorbenen Mitglieder der Societ\u00e4t der musikalischen Wissenschafften\", including: (St\u00f6lzel's obituary, pp.&nbsp;143\u2013157:) \"B.\", and (Bach's obituary, pp.&nbsp;158\u2013176:) \"C. |trans-title= |url=https://archive.org/stream/bub_gb_lfQ4AAAAIAAJ#page/n1008/mode/2up |journal={{ill|Musikalische Bibliothek|de}} |language=de |location=Leipzig |publisher=Mizlerischer B\u00fccherverlag |volume=IV |issue=1 |pages=129\u2013176 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |date=1890 |editor1-last=Naumann |editor1-first=Ernst |editor1-link=Ernst Naumann |title=Joh. Seb. Bach: \"Bist du bei mir\" (Aus dem gr\u00f6ssern Klavierb\u00fcchlein f. A. Magd. Bach) |trans-title=Joh. Seb. Bach: \"Bist du bei mir\" (from the larger keyboard booklet f. A. Magd. Bach |url= |series=Liederkreis: Sammlung vorz\u00fcglicher Lieder und Ges\u00e4nge f\u00fcr eine Stimme mit Begleitung des Pianoforte |language=de |volume=3 |location=Leipzig |publisher=[[Breitkopf & H\u00e4rtel]] |id=271 |ref=harv }}\n*{{cite book |date=1992 |chapter=Song Texts |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hPnPKwYSOKsC&pg=PA46 |editor1-last=Palmer |editor1-first=Willard A. |editor1-link=Willard Palmer |title=Selections from Anna Magdalena's Notebook |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hPnPKwYSOKsC |edition=2nd |publisher=[[Alfred Music]] |pages=46ff |isbn=9781457442704 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last1=Pfau |first1=Marc-Roderich |date=2008 |chapter=Ein unbekanntes Leipziger Kantatentextheft aus dem Jahr 1735: Neues zum Thema Bach und St\u00f6lzel |trans-chapter=An unknown Leipzig cantata text publication from the year 1735: News regarding Bach and St\u00f6lzel |chapter-url=https://journals.qucosa.de/ejournals/bjb/article/view/1899 |editor1-last=Wollny |editor1-first=Peter |editor1-link=Peter Wollny  |title=Bach-Jahrbuch 2008 |trans-title=Bach Yearbook 2008 |url=https://journals.qucosa.de/ejournals/bjb/issue/view/169 |series=[[Bach-Jahrbuch]] |language=de |volume=94 |others=[[Neue Bachgesellschaft]] |location=Leipzig |publisher={{ill|Evangelische Verlagsanstalt|de}} |pages=99\u2013122 |doi=10.13141/bjb.v2008 |isbn=978-3-374-02668-5 |issn=0084-7682 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last1=Potter |first1=John |author-link1=John Potter (musician) |date=2017 |chapter=Beggar at the Door: The Rise and Fall of Portamento in Singing |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1S8rDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA401 |editor1-last=Milsom |editor1-first=David |editor1-link= |title=Classical and Romantic Music |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1S8rDwAAQBAJ |publisher=Routledge |pages=401\u2013428 |isbn=9781351571753 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last1=Schabalina |first1=Tatjana |date=2008 |chapter=''Texte zur Music'' in Sankt Petersburg: Neue Quellen zur Leipziger Musikgeschichte sowie zur Kompositions- und Auff\u00fchrungst\u00e4tigkeit Johann Sebastian Bachs |trans-chapter={{lang|de|Texte zur Music}} in [[Saint Petersburg]]: New sources on Leipzig's music history, including on Johann Sebastian Bach's compository and performatory practices |chapter-url=https://journals.qucosa.de/ejournals/bjb/article/view/1898 |editor1-last=Wollny |editor1-first=Peter |editor1-link=Peter Wollny  |title=Bach-Jahrbuch 2008 |trans-title=Bach Yearbook 2008 |url=https://journals.qucosa.de/ejournals/bjb/issue/view/169 |series=[[Bach-Jahrbuch]] |language=de |volume=94 |others=[[Neue Bachgesellschaft]] |location=Leipzig |publisher={{ill|Evangelische Verlagsanstalt|de}} |pages=33\u201398 |doi=10.13141/bjb.v2008 |isbn=978-3-374-02668-5 |issn=0084-7682 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last1=Stockigt |first1=Janice B. |date=2013 |chapter=Bach's ''Missa'' BWV 232<sup>I</sup> in the context of Catholic Mass settings in Dresden, 1729\u20131733 |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZbT1AAAAQBAJ&pg=PA39 |editor1-last=Tomita |editor1-first=Yo |editor1-link=wikidata:Q11457180 |editor2-last=Leaver |editor2-first=Robin A. |editor2-link= |editor3-last=Smaczny |editor3-first=Jan |editor3-link= |title=Exploring Bach's B-minor Mass |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZbT1AAAAQBAJ |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |pages=39\u201353 |isbn=978-1-107-00790-1 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last1=St\u00f6lzel |first1=Gottfried Heinrich |author-link1=Gottfried Heinrich St\u00f6lzel |date=1740 |chapter=Melch. Hofmann\" and \"St\u00f6ltzel |trans-chapter=\"[[Melchior Hoffmann (composer)|Melch. Hoffmann]]\" and \"[[Gottfried Heinrich St\u00f6lzel|St\u00f6lzel]]\"|chapter-url= |editor1-last=Mattheson |editor1-first=Johann |editor1-link=Johann Mattheson |title=[[scores:Grundlage einer Ehren-Pforte (Mattheson, Johann)|Grundlage einer Ehren-Pforte]] |trans-title= |url= |language=de |location=Hamburg |publisher=Mattheson |pages=117\u2013119 and 342\u2013347 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite web |url=http://homepages.bw.edu/bachbib/script/bach1ct.pl?0=Bitter%2C+Carl+Hermann&3=&12=&4=&5=&6=&8=&sorting=chronologically+%28table%29&maxlimit=300&datefilter=1&Limit=%28select+filters%29 |title=Author : Bitter, Carl Hermann (chronological table) |date=30 December 2018 |editor-last=Tomita |editor-first=Yo |editor= |editor-link=:fr:Y\u014d Tomita |website=Bach Bibliography |publisher=Queen's University Belfast |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |date=1894 |editor1-last=Waldersee |editor1-first=Paul |editor1-link=:de:Paul von Waldersee |title=[[scores:Bach-Gesellschaft Ausgabe (Bach, Johann Sebastian)#Band 43.2. Musikst\u00fccke in den Notenb\u00fcchern der Anna Magdalena Bach|Musikst\u00fccke in den Notenb\u00fcchern der Anna Magdalena Bach]] |trans-title=Musical pieces in the notebooks of Anna Magdalena Bach |url= |series=[[Bach-Gesellschaft Ausgabe]] |language=de |volume=43.2 |location=Leipzig |publisher=[[Breitkopf & H\u00e4rtel]] |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last1=Wolff |first1=Christoph |author-link1=Christoph Wolff |date=2002 |title=Johann Sebastian Bach: The Learned Musician |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ronZdkhQouMC |edition=paperback |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=0199248842 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Wollny |first1=Peter |author-link1=Peter Wollny |date=2008 |chapter=''Bekennen will ich seinen Namen'': Authentizit\u00e4t, Bestimmung und Kontext der Arie BWV&nbsp;200. Anmerkungen zu Johann Sebastian Bachs Rezeption von Werken Gottfried Heinrich St\u00f6lzels |trans-chapter=''Bekennen will ich seinen Namen'': authenticity, purpose and context of the aria [[BWV&nbsp;200]]. Annotations regarding Johann Sebastian Bach's reception of Gottfried Heinrich St\u00f6lzel's works |chapter-url=https://journals.qucosa.de/ejournals/bjb/article/view/1900 |title=Bach-Jahrbuch 2008 |trans-title=Bach Yearbook 2008 |url=https://journals.qucosa.de/ejournals/bjb/issue/view/169 |series=[[Bach-Jahrbuch]] |language=de |volume=94 |others=[[Neue Bachgesellschaft]] |location=Leipzig |publisher={{ill|Evangelische Verlagsanstalt|de}} |pages=123\u2013158 |doi=10.13141/bjb.v2008 |isbn=978-3-374-02668-5 |issn=0084-7682 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |date=1892 |editor1-last=W\u00fcllner |editor1-first=Franz |editor1-link=Franz W\u00fcllner |title=[[scores:Bach-Gesellschaft Ausgabe (Bach, Johann Sebastian)#Band 39. Motetten, Chor\u00e4le und Lieder|Motetten, Chor\u00e4le und Lieder]] |trans-title=Motets, chorales and songs |url= |series=[[Bach-Gesellschaft Ausgabe]] |language=de |volume=39 |location=Leipzig |publisher=[[Breitkopf & H\u00e4rtel]] |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last1=Yearsley |first1=David |author-link1=:nl:David Yearsley |date=2019 |title=Sex, Death, and Minuets: Anna Magdalena Bach and Her Musical Notebooks |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8bGhDwAAQBAJ |publisher=[[University of Chicago Press]] |isbn=9780226617848 |ref=harv }}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://allofbach.com/en/bwv/bwv-508/ Bist du bei mir, BWV 508]: performance by the [[Netherlands Bach Society]] (video and background information)\n* {{IMSLP|work=Songs and Arias, BWV 439-518 (Bach, Johann Sebastian)#Songs and arias from Notenbuch der Anna Magdalena Bach, BWV 508\u2013518|cname=Songs and arias from Notenbuch der Anna Magdalena Bach, BWV 508\u2013518}}\n* {{IMSLP|work=Diomedes (St\u00f6lzel, Gottfried Heinrich)|cname=\"Bist du bei mir\" (from St\u00f6lzel's ''Diomedes'')}}\n* [http://artsongcentral.com/2007/bach-attr-bist-du-bei-mir/ \"Bist du bei mir\"], details, including sheet music\n* [http://www.mutopiaproject.org/cgibin/make-table.cgi?preview=1&searchingfor=Bist&Composer=BachJS&Instrument=&Style=&timelength=1&timeunit=week&lilyversion= \"Bist du bei mir\"] at the [[Mutopia Project]]\n* {{YouTube|id=QYTo4GMWSDc|title=\"Bist du bei mir\"}}, [[Elisabeth Schwarzkopf]], [[Gerald Moore]], [[Angel Records]] 35023\n\n{{Bach spurious}}\n{{Portal bar|Classical music}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1718 compositions]]\n[[Category:1725 compositions]]\n[[Category:Bach: spurious and doubtful works]]\n[[Category:Arias in German]]\n[[Category:Soprano arias]]\n", "text_old": "{{Listen|type=music|filename=Hmv-db2291-32-4808-2wx767.ogg|title=\"Bist du bei mir\" (BWV 508)|description=Performed by soprano [[Elisabeth Schumann]], 1934}}\n\"'''{{Lang|de|Bist du bei mir, geh ich mit Freuden|italic=no}}'''\" (If you are with me, I go with joy) is an [[aria]] from [[Gottfried Heinrich St\u00f6lzel]]'s opera ''Diomedes'', which was first staged staged on 16 November 1718. The aria is best known as \"{{Lang|de|Bist du bei mir|italic=no}}\", [[Bach-Werke-Verzeichnis|BWV]]&nbsp;508, a version for voice and [[basso continuo|continuo]] found as No. 25 in the 1725 ''[[Notebook for Anna Magdalena Bach]]''.\n\n==History==\nGottfried Heinrich St\u00f6lzel's opera ''Diomedes'' was staged in [[Bayreuth]] in November 1718.{{sfn|Hegen|2018|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=X81-DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA15 15]}}{{sfn|Gl\u00f6ckner et al.|2002|pp=173\u2013174}}{{sfn|Mizler|1754|p=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_lfQ4AAAAIAAJ/page/n1030 151]}}{{sfn|St\u00f6lzel|1740|p=[https://archive.org/details/grundlageeinereh00matt/page/346 346]}} There has been some speculation how one of its arias, \"{{Lang|de|Bist du bei mir|italic=no}}\", came to be known in the household of the Bachs in mid-1730s [[Leipzig]], when [[Anna Magdalena Bach]], [[Johann Sebastian Bach|Johann Sebastian]]'s wife, copied an arrangement of the aria in her second notebook.{{sfn|Gl\u00f6ckner et al.|2002|p=174}} 21st-century scholarship has shown that, mainly in the period from the mid 1720s to the mid 1730s, at least several dozens, maybe even over a hundred, of compositions by St\u00f6lzel were adopted by Bach or his family members in their public and private music practices.{{sfn|Schabalina|2008|pp=83\u201384}}{{sfn|Pfau|2008|pp=111\u2013115}}{{sfn|Wollny|2008|pp=135\u2013146}}{{sfn|Gl\u00f6ckner|2009|p=103}} Only indirect evidence has come to light how such music was transferred from St\u00f6lzel to the Bachs.{{sfn|Gl\u00f6ckner et al.|2002|p=174}}{{sfn|Pfau|2008|pp=111\u2013115}}{{sfn|Schabalina|2008|p=80}}{{sfn|Gl\u00f6ckner|2009|p=102}} Bach and St\u00f6lzel were in the same places at different times, and shared acquaintances, but whether they met in person can only be surmised.{{sfn|Gl\u00f6ckner|2009|p=102}}{{sfn|Ahrens|2007|p=46}}\n\n===1707\u20131732===\n[[File:Orchestral version of St\u00f6lzel's Bist du bei mir (1st system).png|thumb|upright=1.35|First system of the orchestral version of St\u00f6lzel's \"{{Lang|de|Bist du bei mir|italic=no}}\", as copied around 1723.]]\n[[File:Orchestral version of St\u00f6lzel's Bist du bei mir (2nd to 4th system).png|thumb|upright=1.35|Orchestral version of St\u00f6lzel's \"{{Lang|de|Bist du bei mir|italic=no}}\" (2nd to 4th system)]]\n[[File:Orchestral version of St\u00f6lzel's Bist du bei mir (5th and 6th system).png|thumb|upright=1.35|Orchestral version of St\u00f6lzel's \"{{Lang|de|Bist du bei mir|italic=no}}\" (5th and 6th system)]]\nFrom 1707 to 1710 St\u00f6lzel was a student at [[Leipzig University]]. At that time, [[Melchior Hoffmann (composer)|Melchior Hoffmann]] was conductor of the [[Collegium Musicum]] founded by [[Georg Philipp Telemann|Telemann]], which had [[Johann Georg Pisendel]] as its [[concert master]]. Hoffmann was {{lang|la|[[director musices]]}} of the [[New Church (Leipzig)|New Church]] ({{lang de|Neue Kirche}}), and his operas were performed in the {{ill|Oper am Br\u00fchl|de|Oper am Br\u00fchl (Leipzig)|lt=''Oper am Br\u00fchl''}} ({{translation|Opera at the [[Br\u00fchl (Leipzig)|Br\u00fchl]]}}) when it reopened in 1708. St\u00f6lzel, eager to cultivate his interest in music, visited such venues of Leipzig's high-quality music life. Eventually he became an assistant of Hoffmann, initially as copyist, and later, shortly before leaving Leipzig, he saw his first compositions performed under Hoffmann's direction.{{sfn|Gl\u00f6ckner et al.|2002|p=174}}{{sfn|Mizler|1754|pp=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_lfQ4AAAAIAAJ/page/n1023 144\u2013145]}}{{sfn|St\u00f6lzel|1740|pp=[https://archive.org/details/grundlageeinereh00matt/page/117 117]\u2013[https://archive.org/details/grundlageeinereh00matt/page/119 119], [https://archive.org/details/grundlageeinereh00matt/page/344 344]}}\n\nBach visited the court at [[Gotha]] in 1711 and 1717.{{sfn|Ahrens|2007|p=46}} In 1711 he had been hired as performer on the organ, and during the second of these documented visits he performed his so-called {{lang|de|[[Weimarer Passion]]}} during [[Holy Week]].{{sfn|Ahrens|2007|pp=45\u201354}} St\u00f6lzel moved to Bayreuth in 1717, where he was appointed to write church music for the second centenary of [[Reformation Day]] (31&nbsp;October).{{sfn|Mizler|1754|p=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_lfQ4AAAAIAAJ/page/n1030 151]}}{{sfn|St\u00f6lzel|1740|p=[https://archive.org/details/grundlageeinereh00matt/page/346 346]}} For the 39th birthday of [[George William, Margrave of Brandenburg-Bayreuth]] (16&nbsp;November) he composed a theatrical [[serenata]], ''Der Liebe Sieges- und Friedes-Palmen''.{{sfn|Hegen|2018|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=X81-DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA15 15]}}{{sfn|Mizler|1754|p=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_lfQ4AAAAIAAJ/page/n1030 151]}}{{sfn|St\u00f6lzel|1740|p=[https://archive.org/details/grundlageeinereh00matt/page/346 346]}} For the Margrave's next birthday he wrote {{Lang|de|Diomedes oder die triumphierende Unschuld}} ({{translation|Diomedes or the triumphant innocence}}), a large-scale opera which was staged on {{nowrap|16 November 1718}}.{{sfn|Hegen|2018|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=X81-DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA15 15]}}{{sfn|Gl\u00f6ckner et al.|2002|pp=173\u2013174}}{{sfn|Mizler|1754|p=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_lfQ4AAAAIAAJ/page/n1030 151]}}{{sfn|St\u00f6lzel|1740|p=[https://archive.org/details/grundlageeinereh00matt/page/346 346]}} Before moving to Gotha the next year, where he would remain for the rest of his life, St\u00f6lzel still composed one further birthday serenata for the Margrave in Bayreuth.{{sfn|Mizler|1754|p=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_lfQ4AAAAIAAJ/page/n1030 151]}}{{sfn|Ahrens|2007|p=45}}\n\nIn 1720, three years before he became {{lang|de|[[Thomaskantor]]}} in Leipzig, Johann Sebastian Bach started the [[Klavierb\u00fcchlein f\u00fcr Wilhelm Friedemann Bach|''Klavierb\u00fcchlein'' (keyboard-booklet) for his eldest son Wilhelm Friedemann]].{{sfn|Klavierb\u00fcchlein f\u00fcr W. F. Bach (US-NHub Music Deposit) at Bach Digital}} Some years later [[Wilhelm Friedemann Bach|Wilhelm Friedemann]] copied a four-[[movement (music)|movement]] keyboard suite by St\u00f6lzel in this notebook, to which his father added a trio ([[BWV&nbsp;929]]).{{sfn|Schabalina|2008|pp=83\u201384}}{{sfn|Klavierb\u00fcchlein f\u00fcr W. F. Bach (US-NHub Music Deposit) at Bach Digital}}{{sfn|D\u00fcrr|Kobayashi|1998|pp=391\u2013392}} In 1725 Johann Sebastian started the second notebook for his second wife Anna Magdalena.{{sfn|Gl\u00f6ckner et al.|2002|pp=173\u2013174}} In the mean while he had assumed his position of cantor and music director in Leipzig: among many responsibilities that came with that title, music in the New Church now resorted under him.{{sfn|Wolff|2002|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=ronZdkhQouMC&pg=PA237 237\u2013253]}} From 1729 he also became director of the Collegium Musicum founded by Telemann.{{sfn|Wolff|2002|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=ronZdkhQouMC&pg=PA351 351ff]}}\n\nMeanwhile in Gotha, St\u00f6lzel had presented his first [[Passion oratorio]], ''[[Ein L\u00e4mmlein geht und tr\u00e4gt die Schuld (St\u00f6lzel)|Ein L\u00e4mmlein geht und tr\u00e4gt die Schuld]]'', in Holy Week of 1720,{{sfn|Schabalina|2008|p=79}} and composed a new [[cantata cycle]] every few years, among which:{{sfn|Mizler|1754|p=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_lfQ4AAAAIAAJ/page/n1031 152]}}\n* in the early 1720s a setting of [[Benjamin Schmolck]]'s ''String-Music'' ({{lang|de|Saitenspiel}}) cantata [[libretto]] cycle.{{sfn|Pfau|2008|pp=106, 110}}\n* for the 1731\u201332 [[liturgical year]], a setting of Schmolck's ''Namebook'' ({{lang|de|Namenbuch}}) cantata libretto cycle.{{sfn|Gl\u00f6ckner|2009|p=96}}\n\n===1733\u20131754===\nWhen [[Augustus the Strong]] died on {{nowrap|1 February 1733}}, a period of mourning was declared in his realm, which included Saxony.{{sfn|Gl\u00f6ckner|2009|p=100}}{{sfn|Schabalina|2008|p=78}} During this period, lasting from [[Church cantata#Second Sunday before Lent (Sexagesima)|Sexagesima Sunday]] (15&nbsp;February) to the [[Church cantata#Fourth Sunday after Trinity (Trinity IV)|fourth Sunday after Trinity]] (28&nbsp;June), no concerted music was to be performed in church services.{{sfn|Gl\u00f6ckner|2009|p=100}}{{sfn|Schabalina|2008|p=78}} Johann Sebastian Bach used the period to compose [[Mass for the Dresden court (Bach)|his Mass for the Dresden court]].{{sfn|Stockigt|2013}} He may have had the musicians of the [[Dresden]] court orchestra in mind when composing this extended setting: one of these musicians was its then-time concert master Pisendel, with whom Bach had been acquainted since before St\u00f6lzel had known him as concert master of Hoffmann's orchestra.{{sfn|Stockigt|2013}}\n\nEarly July 1733, Bach was still completing the composition, and the performance parts he intended to send to Dresden.{{sfn|Stockigt|2013}} Around this time, there are the earliest documented signs he used cantatas composed by St\u00f6lzel for performance in Leipzig.{{sfn|Gl\u00f6ckner|2009|pp=98\u2013102}} He may have performed two cantatas from St\u00f6lzel's ''Namebook'' cycle, for the fifth and sixth Sunday after Trinity, in July 1733: his copies of these cantatas date from around this time.{{sfn|Gl\u00f6ckner|2009|pp=98\u2013102}} He performed St\u00f6lzel's ''Ein L\u00e4mmlein geht und tr\u00e4gt die Schuld'' on Good Friday {{nowrap|23 April 1734}}, and likely St\u00f6lzel's entire ''String-Music'' cantata cycle from 1735 to 1736.{{sfn|Schabalina|2008|pp=83\u201384}}{{sfn|Pfau|2008|pp=111\u2013115}}{{sfn|Wollny|2008|pp=129\u2013146}}{{sfn|Gl\u00f6ckner|2009|pp=95, 102}} Around the same time, that is, likely somewhere between 1734 and 1740, Anna Magdalena Bach entered a version for voice and continuo of \"{{Lang|de|Bist du bei mir|italic=no}}\", an aria from St\u00f6lzel's 1718 ''Diomedes'' opera, in her second notebook.{{sfn|Gl\u00f6ckner et al.|2002|pp=173\u2013174}}{{sfn|Schabalina|2008|pp=83\u201384}}{{sfn|Gl\u00f6ckner|2009|p=103}}<ref name=\"BWV508RISM\">{{RISM|467022526}}.</ref>\n\nThat was not the end of Bach's dealings with St\u00f6lzel's music: in the early 1740s he reworked an aria of St\u00f6lzel's ''Ein L\u00e4mmlein geht und tr\u00e4gt die Schuld'' to [[Bekennen will ich seinen Namen, BWV 200|''Bekennen will ich seinen Namen'', BWV&nbsp;200]].{{sfn|Gl\u00f6ckner|2009|p=103}}{{sfn|Wollny|2008|pp=125\u2013129}} St\u00f6lzel acquiring music composed by Bach is documented in 1747, when he bought a copy of [[The Musical Offering|Bach's ''Musical Offering'']] for Gotha, less than a month after its publication.{{sfn|Ahrens|2007|pp=58\u201360}} Both St\u00f6lzel and Bach joined [[Lorenz Christoph Mizler]]'s exclusive {{ill|Mizler's Music Society|de|Correspondierende Societ\u00e4t der musicalischen Wissenschaften|lt=Society of Musical Sciences}}: St\u00f6lzel in 1739, and Bach in 1746.{{sfn|Mizler|1754}} After they died, St\u00f6lzel in 1749 and Bach in 1750, their obituaries were published in 1754, in the same issue of the Society's organ, the {{ill|Musikalische Bibliothek|de|lt=''Musikalische Bibliothek''}}.{{sfn|Mizler|1754}}\n\n==Text and music==\nIn its 18th-century manuscripts \"{{Lang|de|Bist du bei mir|italic=no}}\" is a [[da capo aria]] for [[soprano]] in [[E-flat major]], in {{music|time|3|4}} [[time signature|time]].<ref name=\"BWV508RISM\" /><ref name=\"BdbmRISM\">[https://opac.rism.info/search?id=469080810 Diomedes (Excerpts): \"Bist du bei mir geh ich mit Freuden\"] at [[RISM]] website.</ref>{{sfn|Gl\u00f6ckner et al.|2002|p=173}} Its lyrics also survive in the printed libretto of St\u00f6lzel's ''Diomedes'' opera:{{sfn|Gl\u00f6ckner et al.|2002|pp=173\u2013174}}\n{{Verse translation|lang=de|Bist du bei mir, geh ich mit Freuden\n&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;zum Sterben und zu meiner Ruh.\nAch, wie vergn\u00fcgt w\u00e4r so mein Ende,\nes dr\u00fcckten deine sch\u00f6nen H\u00e4nde\nmir die getreuen Augen zu.|If you are with me, then I will go gladly\n&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;unto [my] death and to my rest.\nAh, how pleasing were my end,\nif your dear hands then\nshut my faithful eyes!|attr1=[https://www.bach-digital.de/receive/BachDigitalWork_work_00000579?XSL.Style=detail&lang=en Lyrics of \"Bist du bei mir\"] at [[Bach Digital]].|attr2=Translation}}\nTranslations of the aria's text have been published, for instance, by [[Novello & Co|Novello]] and by [[Alfred Music]], and at [[The LiederNet Archive]].{{sfn|Barry|1894}}{{sfn|Palmer|1992|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=hPnPKwYSOKsC&pg=PA47 47]}}{{sfn|Ezust|2014}}\n\n===St\u00f6lzel's ''Diomedes''===\n{{see also|Gottfried Heinrich St\u00f6lzel#Operas}}\nTwo sources from the first quarter of the 18th century document text and music of St\u00f6lzel's ''Diomedes'' opera:{{sfn|Gl\u00f6ckner et al.|2002|pp=172\u2013174}}\n* A libretto printed for the first performance of the opera (16 November 1718 in Bayreuth).{{sfn|Hegen|2018|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=X81-DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA15 15]}}{{sfn|Gl\u00f6ckner et al.|2002|pp=173\u2013174}}\n* A manuscript copy, dated to {{circa|1723}}, containing an orchestral score of five arias by St\u00f6lzel, the only known extant music of the opera.{{sfn|Gl\u00f6ckner et al.|2002|pp=172\u2013174}}\nThe libretto specifies the performance venue as \"{{lang|de|auf dem gro\u00dfen Theatro}}\" ({{translation|at the grand theatre}}), where only some of the more remarkable Bayreuth theatrical productions of the time were staged.{{sfn|Hegen|2018|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=X81-DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA15 15]}}{{sfn|Gl\u00f6ckner et al.|2002|pp=173\u2013174}} The libretto names no composer.{{sfn|Hegen|2018|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=X81-DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA15 15]}} In his autobiography, St\u00f6lzel describes the opera as \"{{lang|de|von meiner Arbeit}}\" ({{translation|\"made by me\"}}).{{sfn|St\u00f6lzel|1740|p=[https://archive.org/details/grundlageeinereh00matt/page/346 346]}} Also the 1720s manuscript copy of five arias mentions him as composer.{{sfn|Gl\u00f6ckner et al.|2002|p=173}} St\u00f6lzel often wrote his own librettos.{{sfn|St\u00f6lzel|1740|pp=[https://archive.org/details/grundlageeinereh00matt/page/343 343\u2013347]}} As far as known, the opera is his most extended composition: it contains over seventy arias, eight duets and six choruses, totalling over hundred movements.{{sfn|Gl\u00f6ckner et al.|2002|p=174}}\n\nThe 1720s manuscript with the five arias does not name the instruments for which it is scored: these are assumed to be [[string section|strings]], that is [[violin]]s (vl), [[viola]] (va) and [[basso continuo]] (bc). The [[soprano clef]] for the singer indicates a soprano voice for all arias. They are in different [[key (music)|key]]s, and all of them are da capo arias. The fourth aria, that is \"{{Lang|de|Bist du bei mir|italic=no}}\", is in E-flat major (although notated with only two flats at the clef), and has the most extended instrumentation: first violin (vl1), second violin (vl2), viola and continuo. It is also the only aria with a [[dynamics (music)|dynamics]] indicator: {{lang|it|semper piano}} (soft throughout). Apart from the second aria, which seems to be an addition to the 7th scene of the 3rd act, all texts of the five arias score correspond with passages of the libretto of 1718, thus the lyrics of these arias can be coupled with the characters of the [[dramatis personae]] of the opera.{{sfn|Gl\u00f6ckner et al.|2002|pp=173\u2013174}}<ref name=\"SBBmanuscript\">[http://resolver.staatsbibliothek-berlin.de/SBB00019D7700000000 (Sammelhandschrift) 11 Geistliche Ges\u00e4nge] at [[Berlin State Library]] website, [http://resolver.staatsbibliothek-berlin.de/SBB00019D7700000129 pp.&nbsp;129\u2013131].</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ Extant arias of St\u00f6lzel's ''Diomedes''{{sfn|Gl\u00f6ckner et al.|2002|pp=173\u2013174}}<ref name=\"11SacredSongsRISM\">[https://opac.rism.info/search?id=469080800 Collection: 11 Sacred songs] at [[RISM]] website.</ref> \n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | #\n! scope=\"col\" | text incipit\n! scope=\"col\" | character\n! scope=\"col\" | scene\n! scope=\"col\" | signature\n! scope=\"col\" | instruments\n|-\n| {{0}}1.\n| Es ist die Ursach' meines Leidens\n| Diomedes\n| data-sort-value=\"II 11\" | Act&nbsp;II, sc.&nbsp;11\n| [[F&nbsp;major]]; {{music|time|3|4}}\n| vl va bc<ref>{{RISM|469080807}}.</ref>\n|-\n| {{0}}2.\n| Geht ihr K\u00fcsse geht ihr Blicke\n| Mosthenes\n| data-sort-value=\"III 07\" | Act&nbsp;III, sc.&nbsp;7\n| [[G&nbsp;major]]; {{music|time|3|8}}\n| vl bc<ref>{{RISM|469080808}}.</ref>\n|-\n| {{0}}3.\n| Mein Gl\u00fccke steht in deinen H\u00e4nden\n| Copele\n| data-sort-value=\"II 06\" | Act&nbsp;II, sc.&nbsp;6\n| [[A&nbsp;major]]; {{music|time|3|4}}\n| vl va bc<ref>{{RISM|469080809}}.</ref>\n|-\n| {{0}}4.\n| '''Bist du bei mir geh ich mit Freuden'''\n| Diomedes\n| data-sort-value=\"III 08\" | Act&nbsp;III, sc.&nbsp;8\n| [[E\u266d&nbsp;major]]; {{music|time|3|4}}\n| vl1 vl2 va bc<ref name=\"BdbmRISM\" />\n|-\n| {{0}}5.\n| Sage mir doch wertes Gl\u00fccke\n| Desania\n| data-sort-value=\"I 05\" | Act&nbsp;I, sc.&nbsp;5\n| [[A&nbsp;minor]]; {{music|time|3|8}}\n| vl va bc<ref>{{RISM|469080811}}.</ref>\n|}\n\n===Anna Magdalena Bach's ''Notenb\u00fcchlein''===\n{{see also|Notebook for Anna Magdalena Bach}}\n[[Anna Magdalena Wilcke]] was an accomplished vocalist when she married Johann Sebastian Bach in 1721, around which time she was hired as a singer by his employer at [[K\u00f6then (Anhalt)|K\u00f6then]].{{sfn|Wolff|2002|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=ronZdkhQouMC&pg=PA216 216]}}{{sfn|Yearsley|2019|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=8bGhDwAAQBAJ&pg=PR19 XIX]}} A year later, her first notebook was started: it contains, as far as extant, only keyboard music, most of it written down by Johann Sebastian.{{sfn|Yearsley|2019|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=8bGhDwAAQBAJ&pg=PR19 XIX\u2013XXI]}}{{sfn|1. Klavierb\u00fcchlein der A. M. Bach, 1722 (D-B Mus.ms. Bach P 224) at Bach Digital}} The first entries in her second notebook were, like the first entries in Wilhelm Friedemann's 1720 notebook, keyboard compositions by Johann Sebastian, written down by the composer.{{sfn|Klavierb\u00fcchlein f\u00fcr W. F. Bach (US-NHub Music Deposit) at Bach Digital}}{{sfn|2. Notenb\u00fcchlein der A. M. Bach, 1725 (D-B Mus. ms. Bach P 225) at Bach Digital}} In the 1725 notebook these are followed by around ten short keyboard pieces by various composers, among which [[Christian Petzold (composer)|Christian Petzold]]'s [[Minuet in G major, BWV Anh. 114|Minuet in G&nbsp;major (BWV&nbsp;Anh.&nbsp;114)]], written down by Anna Magdalena without composer indication.{{sfn|2. Notenb\u00fcchlein der A. M. Bach, 1725 (D-B Mus. ms. Bach P 225) at Bach Digital}} The next pieces, BWV&nbsp;510\u2013512, are the first compositions for singing that appear in Anna Magdalena's notebooks.{{sfn|2. Notenb\u00fcchlein der A. M. Bach, 1725 (D-B Mus. ms. Bach P 225) at Bach Digital}}<ref>[http://resolver.staatsbibliothek-berlin.de/SBB0001D81000000000 Klavierb\u00fcchlein f\u00fcr Anna Magdalena Bach (1725)] at [[Berlin State Library]] website.</ref>\n\nThe pieces in Anna Magdalena's 1725 notebook were written down by eight different scribes, that is, apart from Johann Sebastian and Anna Magdalena, [[Carl Philipp Emanuel Bach|Carl Philipp Emanuel]] (the second son from Johann Sebastian's first marriage), two sons of Johann Sebastian and Anna Magdalena ([[Johann Christoph Friedrich Bach|Johann Christoph Friedrich]] and [[Johann Christian Bach|Johann Christian]]), Bernhard Dietrich Ludewig (known to have worked as a copyist of some choral works for Bach), and two further writers who have not been identified.{{sfn|2. Notenb\u00fcchlein der A. M. Bach, 1725 (D-B Mus. ms. Bach P 225) at Bach Digital}} Pieces were entered intermittently over a long period of time (e.g., Johann Christian was born in 1735), and their sequence in the manuscript does not reflect the chronology of when they were entered.{{cn|date=January 2020}} The \"Menuet fait par Mons. B\u00f6hm\" (No.&nbsp;21, entered by Johann Sebastian) is the only piece that is attributed to another composer in the manuscript.{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n[[File:AMBII75 - bist du bei mir (p1).png|thumb|upright=1.35|First page of \"{{Lang|de|Bist du bei mir|italic=no}}\", BWV&nbsp;508, as written down by [[Anna Magdalena Bach]].]]\n[[File:AMBII75 - bist du bei mir (p2).png|thumb|upright=1.35|Second page of \"{{Lang|de|Bist du bei mir|italic=no}}\", BWV 508, as written down by Anna Magdalena Bach.]]\nTwo objectives are apparent in Anna Magdalena's second notebook:{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n* it was used for instruction such as the musical education of Bach's younger sons, comparable to how Wilhelm Friedemann's {{lang|de|Klavierb\u00fcchlein}} was in part used for the musical education of his eldest son.{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n* it contained {{lang|de|[[House concert|Hausmusik]]}} ({{literal translation|home-music}}), that is music to be performed in the family circle, such as most of the pieces that are still extant in Anna Magdalena's first notebook.{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n\nNo.&nbsp;25, \"{{Lang|de|Bist du bei mir|italic=no}}\", BWV&nbsp;508, belongs to the second category, along with another dozen pieces of vocal music in the 1725 notebook.{{cn|date=January 2020}} Most of these other vocal compositions ([[List of songs and arias by Johann Sebastian Bach#Songs and arias from the second Notebook for Anna Magdalena Bach (BWV 508\u2013518)|BWV&nbsp;509\u2013518]], [[BWV 299|299]] and [[BWV&nbsp;82|82]]/2\u20133) can, according to the 1998 edition of the {{lang|de|[[Bach-Werke-Verzeichnis]]}} (BWV), be attributed to Johann Sebastian.{{sfn|D\u00fcrr|Kobayashi|1998|pp=86\u201387, 285, 289, 308\u2013309}} Doubts about this attribution have however arisen regarding following arias and [[sacred song]]s:\n* No.&nbsp;12: \"Gib dich zufrieden und sei stille\" (BWV&nbsp;510)<ref>{{BDh|581|0|2019-03-11}}</ref>\n* No.&nbsp;20: \"So oft ich meine Tobackspfeife\" (BWV&nbsp;515) is possibly by Bach's son [[Gottfried Heinrich Bach|Gottfried Heinrich]] according to the 1998 edition of the BWV,{{sfn|D\u00fcrr|Kobayashi|1998|p=308}} but only attributed to the father at the [[Bach Digital]] website.<ref>{{BDh|586|0|2019-03-11}}</ref>\n* No.&nbsp;37: \"Willst du dein Herz mir schenken\" a.k.a. \"Aria di G[i]ovannini\" (BWV&nbsp;518)<ref>{{BDh|590|0|2019-03-11}}</ref>\n* No.&nbsp;40: \"Wie wohl ist mir, o Freund der Seelen\" (BWV&nbsp;517)<ref>{{BDh|589|0|2019-03-11}}</ref>\n* No.&nbsp;41: \"Gedenke doch, mein Geist, zur\u00fccke\" (BWV&nbsp;509)<ref>{{BDh|580|0|2019-03-11}}</ref>\n\nFor many keyboard pieces that were unattributed in Anna Magdalena's 1725 {{lang|de|Notenb\u00fcchlein}}, doubts about authorship had been around for a longer time: twenty such pieces, [[BWV&nbsp;Anh.]]&nbsp;113\u2013132, had been listed in the [[BWV Anh. II|second ''Anhang'']], that is the {{lang|de|[[Anhang (disambiguation)|Anhang]]}} of doubtful compositions, since the 1950 first edition of the BWV catalogue.{{sfn|D\u00fcrr|Kobayashi|1998|pp=459, 465}} Apart from \"{{Lang|de|Bist du bei mir|italic=no}}\", all compositions from the three notebooks (Wilhelm Friedemann's {{lang|de|Klavierb\u00fcchlein}} and both of Anna Magdalena's notebooks) that have been positively identified as being originally composed by another composer than Bach are keyboard pieces.{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n\nIn the notebook \"{{Lang|de|Bist du bei mir|italic=no}}\" is entered on two non-consecutive pages: the first half of the aria is on page 75, and the second half is on page 78: in between, No.&nbsp;26 on pages 76\u201377, is Anna Magdalena's copy of the aria of the ''[[Goldberg Variations]]''.<ref name=\"BWV508RISM\" /> That copy of [[BWV&nbsp;988]]/1 was written down no earlier than 1733\u201334, possibly even only in the 1740s.{{sfn|2. Notenb\u00fcchlein der A. M. Bach, 1725 (D-B Mus. ms. Bach P 225) at Bach Digital}} There are various possibilities as to how the ''Diomedes'' aria became known in the Bach household, including, according to [[Andreas Gl\u00f6ckner]], from scores that once belonged to the {{lang|de|Oper am Br\u00fchl}} (which had bankrupted in 1720), or that \"{{Lang|de|Bist du bei mir|italic=no}}\" simply was a well-known ditty in Leipzig in the second quarter of the 18th century, which Anna Magdalena thought would make a welcome addition to her {{Lang|de|Hausmusik}} collection.{{sfn|Gl\u00f6ckner et al.|2002|p=174}}\n\nLike in the five arias manuscript, the \"{{Lang|de|Bist du bei mir|italic=no}}\" version in Anna Magdalena's notebook is in E-flat major, and uses a soprano clef for the singing voice.<ref name=\"BWV508RISM\" /> A difference in the notation is, however, that Anna Magdalena's manuscript uses three flats at the clef, which is the usual [[key signature]] for a composition in that key.<ref name=\"BWV508RISM\" /> Anna Magdalena likely copied her version from a score that used two flats at the clef.<ref name=\"BWV508RISM\" /> Apart from one measure in the second half of the composition, the melody for the singing voice is identical in both manuscripts.{{sfn|Gl\u00f6ckner et al.|2002|p=173}}<ref name=\"BdbmRISM\" /> The continuo part of the BWV&nbsp;508 version of \"{{Lang|de|Bist du bei mir|italic=no}}\" is more lively and continuous in its voice leading than that of the extant orchestral version of the aria.{{sfn|Gl\u00f6ckner et al.|2002|p=173}}<ref name=\"BdbmRISM\" /> The characteristics of the BWV&nbsp;508 version (and of its extant manuscript), do not prove that Anna Magdalena's husband was the arranger of that version.{{sfn|Gl\u00f6ckner et al.|2002|p=173}}\n\n==Reception==\n<!--Apart from a few arias the music of St\u00f6lzel's ''Diomedes'' is lost. A version for soprano, [[string orchestra|strings]] and continuo of its aria \"{{Lang|de|Bist du bei mir|italic=no}}\" survives in an 18th-century manuscript owned by the [[Sing-Akademie zu Berlin]].-->\n\n===1860s\u20131940s===\nIn 1866, a year after he had published [[Biographies of Johann Sebastian Bach#Bitter's multi-volume biography|his two-volume biography of Johann Sebastian Bach]], [[Carl Hermann Bitter]] published six songs from Anna Magdalena's second {{lang|de|Notenb\u00fcchlein}}, including \"{{Lang|de|Bist du bei mir|italic=no}}\".{{sfn|Yearsley|2019|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=8bGhDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA256 256]}}{{sfn|Tomita|2018}}{{sfn|Bitter|1866}} [[Ernst Naumann]] published the aria separately in 1890, with a keyboard realisation of the accompaniment of his own hand.{{sfn|Naumann|1890}}{{sfn|Hofmeister|1890|p=[http://anno.onb.ac.at/cgi-content/anno-buch?apm=0&aid=1000001&bd=0001890&teil=0203&seite=00000340 340]}} The {{lang|de|[[Bach Gesellschaft]]}} published \"{{Lang|de|Bist du bei mir|italic=no}}\" twice, both in the voice and continuo version as found in Anna Magdalena's notebook:\n* edited by [[Franz W\u00fcllner]], in Vol.&nbsp;39 (1892) of the {{lang|de|Bach-Gesellschaft Ausgabe}} (BGA).{{sfn|W\u00fcllner|1892|pp=309\u2013310}} In his preface, the editor names \"{{Lang|de|Bist du bei mir|italic=no}}\" as one of the most beautiful songs he knows, and attributes it without doubt to Bach.{{sfn|W\u00fcllner|1892|p=LXII}}\n* edited by {{ill|Paul Waldersee|scores|Category:Waldersee, Paul|de|Paul von Waldersee}}, in Vol.&nbsp;43<sup>2</sup> (1894) of the BGA.{{sfn|Waldersee|1894|pp=36\u201337}} This editor is a bit more cautious when attributing the piece to Bach (\"... k\u00f6nnte ... wohl eine Composition Johann Sebastian's sein\" \u2013 {{translation|\"... could ... well be a composition by Johann Sebastian\"}}), while thinking it odd that the lyrics, which rather seem to be spoken by a male character, would be assigned to a female voice.{{sfn|Waldersee|1894|p=XII}}\n[[File:Blanche Marchesi btv1b85969067-p025 (cropped).jpg|thumb|[[Blanche Marchesi]] recorded \"{{Lang|de|Bist du bei mir|italic=no}}\" in 1906.{{sfn|Potter|2017|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=1S8rDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA416 416]}}]]\nAlso in 1894, Novello published ''Three Songs from Anna-Magdalena Bach's Notebooks'', among which \"{{Lang|de|Bist du bei mir|italic=no}}\", with an English translation.{{sfn|Barry|1894}}{{sfn|Yearsley|2019|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=8bGhDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA14 14], [https://books.google.com/books?id=8bGhDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA258 258]}} A story about Bach's family life, published in the same year for a youthful audience, describes the aria as especially captivating among the songs and dances of the notebooks.{{sfn|Yearsley|2019|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=8bGhDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA11 11], [https://books.google.com/books?id=8bGhDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA257 257\u2013258]}} After the publication of several anthologies, all the pieces of the second notebook were published in a single volume in 1904.{{sfn|Yearsley|2019|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=8bGhDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA11 11\u201312], [https://books.google.com/books?id=8bGhDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA258 258]}}{{sfn|Batka|1904}} \"{{Lang|de|Bist du bei mir|italic=no}}\" was recorded in 1906, sung by [[Blanche Marchesi]].{{sfn|Potter|2017|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=1S8rDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA416 416]}}\n\nAround 1915 [[Max Schneider (music historian)|Max Schneider]] discovered the orchestral version of \"{{Lang|de|Bist du bei mir|italic=no}}\", along with four other arias by St\u00f6lzel, in an 18th-century manuscript at the library of the [[Sing-Akademie zu Berlin]].{{sfn|Berkahn|2006|p=40}} At the time, this source was not further explored.{{sfn|Gl\u00f6ckner et al.|2002|p=172}} In the 1920s the aria appeared in fictionalised biographical accounts:{{sfn|Yearsley|2019|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=8bGhDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA13 13\u201318], [https://books.google.com/books?id=8bGhDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA258 258]}}\n* A 1924 story by {{ill|Kurt Arnold Findeisen|de}} depicts Anna Magdalena starting to sing the aria when her husband returns home with the news that the [[Christiane Eberhardine of Brandenburg-Bayreuth|Saxon Electress]] has died (1727).{{sfn|Yearsley|2019|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=8bGhDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA13 13\u201315], [https://books.google.com/books?id=8bGhDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA258 258]}}\n* [[Esther Meynell]]'s ''The Little Chronicle of Magdalena Bach'' (1925) pictures Anna Magdalena as overcome with emotion when she attempts to sing the aria.{{sfn|Yearsley|2019|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=8bGhDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA16 16\u201318], [https://books.google.com/books?id=8bGhDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA258 258]}}\n\n[[Lotte Lehmann]] recorded \"{{Lang|de|Bist du bei mir|italic=no}}\" in 1929.<ref>[https://lottelehmannleague.org/the-lehmann-recordings/ The Lehmann Recordings] at [[Lotte Lehmann League]] website. {{Retrieved|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref> Singers who recorded the aria in the 1930s include [[Elisabeth Schumann]], {{ill|Paula Salomon-Lindberg|de}} and [[Jo Vincent]].<ref>[https://pool.publicdomainproject.org/index.php/Hmv-db2291-32-4808-2wx767 Hmv-db2291-32-4808-2wx767] at [[Public Domain Project]] website. {{Retrieved|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref><ref>{{OCLC|59669412}} {{Retrieved|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref><ref>{{BNF|37827808s}} {{Retrieved|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref> [[Richard Crooks]] sang \"If Thou Be Near\", an English-language version of the aria, on a recording that was released in 1938.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/78_if-thou-be-near-bist-du-bei-mir_richard-crooks-j-s-bach-charles-oconnell-wilfr_gbia0042859b If Thou Be Near (Bist du bei Mir) by Richard Crooks; J. S. Bach; Charles O'Connell; Wilfred Pelletier \u2013 Victor (1912-B)] at [[Internet Archive]] website. {{Retrieved|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref> Another English-language version, \"Be Thou with me\", was sung by [[Isobel Baillie]] on a war-time recording.<ref>{{OCLC|46612450}} {{Retrieved|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref> During the [[Second World War]], the archive of the Berlin Sing-Akademie went lost.<ref name=\"Veit2007\">Patrice Veit. [http://ifha.revues.org/624 \"''EN\u00dfLIN, Wolfram,'' Die Bach-Quellen der SingAkademie zu Berlin. Katalog\"], recension in ''Revue de l'Institut fran\u00e7ais d'histoire en Allemagne'', 2007.</ref> [[Otto Klemperer]]'s orchestral version of the aria was recorded in the 1940s.<ref>[http://www.arkivmusic.com/classical/album.jsp?album_id=654674 J.S. Bach: Magnificat In&nbsp;D; Brandenburg Concerto No.&nbsp;5; Air From Suite No.&nbsp;3; Bist Du Bei Mir] at [[ArkivMusic]] website. {{Retrieved|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref>\n\n===1950s and later===\nIn 1950 [[Wolfgang Schmieder]] listed \"{{Lang|de|Bist du bei mir|italic=no}}\" as a composition by Bach in the first edition of the ''[[Bach-Werke-Verzeichnis]]'', assigning it the number 508 in that catalogue. In 1957 the aria was published in the ''[[New Bach Edition]]'', where its editor, [[Georg von Dadelsen]], mentioned the lost orchestral version in the Critical Commentary volume.{{sfn|Berkahn|2006|pp=40\u201342}}<ref>[[Georg von Dadelsen]], editor. ''[[New Bach Edition]]'', [https://www.baerenreiter.com/en/catalogue/complete-editions/bach-johann-sebastian/nba/series-v/ Series V: Keyboard and Lute Works], Vol. 4: ''The Klavierb\u00fcchlein f\u00fcr Anna Magdalena Bach from 1722 and 1725'', [https://www.baerenreiter.com/en/shop/product/details/BA5008_01/ Score] (1957; <sup>2</sup>1963; <sup>3</sup>1978; <sup>4</sup>2014) and [https://www.baerenreiter.com/en/shop/product/details/BA5008_41/ Critical Commentary] (1957). [[B\u00e4renreiter]].</ref><ref>{{BDh|579|00|2019-06-14|Work|Bist du bei mir (aria) BWV 508}}</ref> The 1998 edition of the Bach-Werke-Verzeichnis kept \"{{Lang|de|Bist du bei mir|italic=no}}\" in the main catalogue (i.e. without moving it to the ''[[BWV Anh.|Anhang]]'' either of the doubtful or of the spurious works), but mentions it was based on a setting by St\u00f6lzel in an inaccessible source.<ref>(BWV<sup>2a</sup>) [[Alfred D\u00fcrr]], Yoshitake Kobayashi (eds.), Kirsten Bei\u00dfwenger. ''Bach Werke Verzeichnis: Kleine Ausgabe, nach der von Wolfgang Schmieder vorgelegten 2. Ausgabe''. Preface in English and German. Wiesbaden: [[Breitkopf & H\u00e4rtel]], 1998. {{ISBN|3765102490}} \u2013 {{ISBN|978-3765102493}}, [https://www.bachmidi.info/kbwv-06.html#p0308 pp.&nbsp;308\u2013309].</ref>\n\nRecordings of the aria from the second half of the 20th century include:\n* [[Elisabeth Schwarzkopf]]'s 1954 recording at [[Abbey Road Studios]] with pianist [[Gerald Moore]],<ref>[http://www.arkivmusic.com/classical/album.jsp?album_id=550072 ''Elisabeth Schwarzkopf \u2013 Perfect Prima Donna''], [[EMI Classics]], Cat. 9184592, at [[ArkivMusic]].</ref>\n\nIn 1999 the lost archive of the [[Sing-Akademie zu Berlin]] was recovered in [[Kiev]].<ref name=\"Veit2007\" /> Nonetheless the manuscript with the five St\u00f6lzel arias was still considered lost as late as 2006.{{sfn|Berkahn|2006|pp=40\u201342}} That same year the manuscript was however described in a publication by the [[Bach Archive]], edited by Wolfram En\u00dflin.<ref name=\"Veit2007\" /><ref name=\"11SacredSongsRISM\" /> In 2009 a full catalogue of the Sing-Akademie's archive was published, in which the manuscript containing the five arias by St\u00f6lzel is indicated as SA&nbsp;808.<ref name=\"Gruyter2009\">Axel Fischer and Matthias Kornemann, editors. [https://books.google.com/books?id=cBfCTlW9R9YC ''The Archive of the Sing-Akademie zu Berlin: Catalogue''.] Walter de Gruyter, 2009. {{ISBN|9783598441745}}, [https://books.google.com/books?id=cBfCTlW9R9YC&pg=PA67 p.&nbsp;67,] [https://books.google.com/books?id=cBfCTlW9R9YC&pg=PA249 249\u2013250] and [https://books.google.com/books?id=cBfCTlW9R9YC&pg=PA687 687\u2013688].</ref> By this time \"{{Lang|de|Bist du bei mir|italic=no}}\" and the four other arias of the SA&nbsp;808 manuscript were identified as belonging to St\u00f6lzel's opera ''Diomedes''.<ref name=\"Gruyter2009\" /> The archive of the Sing-Akademie was transmitted to the [[Berlin State Library]], which made a facsimile of the manuscript containing the ''Diomedes'' arias available on their website.<ref name=\"SBBmanuscript\" /><ref name=\"Veit2007\" />\n\n\"{{Lang|de|Bist du bei mir|italic=no}}\" has become a very popular choice for wedding ceremonies and other such occasions.{{sfn|Berkahn|2006|pp=40\u201342}}<ref name=\"HBrecordings\">[http://www.hbdirect.com/browse_classical.php?composer=S&specific_composer=St%26ouml%3Blzel%2C+Gottfried+Heinrich&v_0=composer&v_1=specific_composer&v_2=specific_work&specific_work=Bist+du+bei+mir St\u00f6lzel, Gottfried Heinrich  \"Bist du bei mir\"] at hbdirect.com.</ref> The question whether the perception and popularity of the piece would have been affected if it would have been identified as St\u00f6lzel's in an earlier stage remains unanswered.{{sfn|Berkahn|2006|pp=40\u201342}}\n\n21st-century recordings of \"Bist du bei mir\" include:\n* A recording by [[Natalie Dessay]] and [[Rolando Villaz\u00f3n]], with an accompaniment for [[piano]], [[violin]]s, and [[cello]] arranged by [[Philippe Rombi]], for the 2005 film ''[[Joyeux No\u00ebl]]''.{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Sources ==\n* {{BDh|1135|0|2020-01-22|Source|1. Klavierb\u00fcchlein der A. M. Bach, 1722 (D-B Mus.ms. Bach P 224)}}\n* {{BDh|1136|0|2020-01-13|Source|2. Notenb\u00fcchlein der A. M. Bach, 1725 (D-B Mus. ms. Bach P 225)}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Ahrens |first1=Christian |date=2007 |chapter=Neue Quellen zu J. S. Bachs Beziehungen nach Gotha |trans-chapter=New sources regarding J.&nbsp;S. Bach's interaction with Gotha |chapter-url=https://journals.qucosa.de/ejournals/bjb/article/view/1816 |editor1-last=Wollny |editor1-first=Peter |editor1-link=Peter Wollny  |title=Bach-Jahrbuch 2007 |trans-title=Bach Yearbook 2007 |url=https://journals.qucosa.de/ejournals/bjb/issue/view/168 |series=[[Bach-Jahrbuch]] |language=de |volume=93 |others=[[Neue Bachgesellschaft]] |location=Leipzig |publisher={{ill|Evangelische Verlagsanstalt|de}} |pages=45\u201360 |doi=10.13141/bjb.v2007 |isbn=978-3-374-02579-4 |issn=0084-7682 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |translator-last1=Hernaman |translator-first1=C.&nbsp;F. |translator-link1= |date=1894 |chapter= |script-chapter= |trans-chapter= |chapter-url= |editor1-last=Barry |editor1-first=Charles Ainslie |editor1-link= |title=Three Songs from Anna-Magdalena Bach's Notebooks |url= |publisher=[[Novello & Co]] |pages= |oclc=1061635218 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |date=1904 |editor1-last=Batka |editor1-first=Richard |editor1-link=:de:Richard Batka |title=Johann Sebastian Bachs Notenb\u00fcchlein f\u00fcr Anna Magdalena Bach (1725) |trans-title=Johann Sebastian Bach's note-booklet for Anna Magdalena Bach (1725) |url= |language=de |location=Munich |publisher=Callwey |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite thesis |last1=Berkahn |first1=Jonathan |author-link1= |date=2006 |title=Wrestling with the German Devil: Five Case Studies in Fugue After J.S. Bach |url=http://hdl.handle.net/10063/1038 |publisher=Victoria University of Wellington |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |date=1866 |editor1-last=Bitter |editor1-first=Carl Hermann |editor1-link=Carl Hermann Bitter |title=Sechs deutsche Lieder von Joh. Seb. Bach |trans-title=Six German Songs by Joh. Seb. Bach |url= |language=de |others=[[Vincenz Lachner|Lachner, Vincenz]] (realisation of piano accompaniment) |location=Berlin |publisher=Bote & G. Bock |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |date=1998 |editor1-last=D\u00fcrr |editor1-first=Alfred |editor1-link=Alfred D\u00fcrr |editor2-last=Kobayashi |editor2-first=Yoshitake |title=[[Bach-Werke-Verzeichnis|Bach Werke Verzeichnis: Kleine Ausgabe \u2013 Nach der von Wolfgang Schmieder vorgelegten 2. Ausgabe]] |trans-title=Bach Works Catalogue: Small Edition \u2013 After Wolfgang Schmieder's 