n)#Band 39. Motetten, Chor\u00e4le und Lieder|Motetten, Chor\u00e4le und Lieder]] |trans-title=Motets, chorales and songs |url= |series=[[Bach-Gesellschaft Ausgabe]] |language=de |volume=39 |location=Leipzig |publisher=[[Breitkopf & H\u00e4rtel]] |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last1=Yearsley |first1=David |author-link1=:nl:David Yearsley |date=2019 |title=Sex, Death, and Minuets: Anna Magdalena Bach and Her Musical Notebooks |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8bGhDwAAQBAJ |publisher=[[University of Chicago Press]] |isbn=9780226617848 |ref=harv }}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://allofbach.com/en/bwv/bwv-508/ Bist du bei mir, BWV 508]: performance by the [[Netherlands Bach Society]] (video and background information)\n* {{IMSLP|work=Songs and Arias, BWV 439-518 (Bach, Johann Sebastian)#Songs and arias from Notenbuch der Anna Magdalena Bach, BWV 508\u2013518|cname=Songs and arias from Notenbuch der Anna Magdalena Bach, BWV 508\u2013518}}\n* {{IMSLP|work=Diomedes (St\u00f6lzel, Gottfried Heinrich)|cname=\"Bist du bei mir\" (from St\u00f6lzel's ''Diomedes'')}}\n* [http://artsongcentral.com/2007/bach-attr-bist-du-bei-mir/ \"Bist du bei mir\"], details, including sheet music\n* [http://www.mutopiaproject.org/cgibin/make-table.cgi?preview=1&searchingfor=Bist&Composer=BachJS&Instrument=&Style=&timelength=1&timeunit=week&lilyversion= \"Bist du bei mir\"] at the [[Mutopia Project]]\n* {{YouTube|id=QYTo4GMWSDc|title=\"Bist du bei mir\"}}, [[Elisabeth Schwarzkopf]], [[Gerald Moore]], [[Angel Records]] 35023\n\n{{Bach spurious}}\n{{Portal bar|Classical music}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1718 compositions]]\n[[Category:1725 compositions]]\n[[Category:Bach: spurious and doubtful works]]\n[[Category:Arias in German]]\n[[Category:Soprano arias]]\n", "name_user": "Alatius", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bist_du_bei_mir"}
{"title_page": "Albert Lincoln Washburn", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n|name              = Albert Lincoln Washburn\n|image             = \n|image_size        = \n|caption           = \n|birth_date        = {{birth date|1911|6|15}}\n|birth_place       = {{nowrap|[[New York City]], New York, U.S.}}\n|death_date        = {{Death date and age|2007|01|30|1911|6|15}}\n|death_place       = [[Seattle]], Washington, U.S.\n|citizenship       = United States\n|nationality       = American\n|field             = [[Geomorphology]]\n|work_institutions = \n|alma_mater        = Yale University \n|doctoral_advisor  = [[Richard Foster Flint]] \n|doctoral_students = \n|known_for         = [[Permafrost]] studies \n|influences        = \n|influenced        = \n|prizes            = [[Swedish Society for Anthropology and Geography#Recipients of the Vega Medal.5B4.5D|Vega Medal]] <small>(1997)</small>\n|religion          = \n|footnotes         = \n|signature         =\n}}\n\n'''Albert Lincoln \"Link\" Washburn''' (1911\u20132007) was an American [[geomorphology|geomorphologist]] studying [[permafrost]]. Washburn was a proficient skier participating in the [[1936 Winter Olympics]]. Much of his work on permafrost was done in the [[Northern Canada|Canadian arctic]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pubs.aina.ucalgary.ca/arctic/Arctic60-2-212.pdf |title=Albert Lincoln Washburn (1911\u20132007) |website=pubs.aina.ucalgary.ca}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links==\n* {{SR/Olympics profile|wa/link-washburn-1|Link Washburn}}\n* {{IOC profile|albert-lincoln-washburn|Albert Lincoln Washburn}}\n* [https://archives-manuscripts.dartmouth.edu/repositories/2/resources/1095 ''Reconnaissance geology of portions of Victoria Island and immediately adjacent regions, Arctic Canada'' Manuscript] at Dartmouth College Library\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Washburn, Albert Lincoln}}\n[[Category:Alpine skiers at the 1936 Winter Olympics]]\n[[Category:American geomorphologists]]\n[[Category:Quaternary geologists]]\n[[Category:1911 births]]\n[[Category:2007 deaths]]\n[[Category:American male alpine skiers]]\n[[Category:Olympic alpine skiers of the United States]]\n\n\n{{US-alpine-skiing-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n|name              = Albert Lincoln Washburn\n|image             = \n|image_size        = \n|caption           = \n|birth_date        = {{birth date|1911|6|15}}\n|birth_place       = {{nowrap|[[New York City]], New York, U.S.}}\n|death_date        = {{Death date and age|2007|01|30|1911|6|15}}\n|death_place       = [[Seattle]], Washington, U.S.\n|citizenship       = United States\n|nationality       = American\n|field             = [[Geomorphology]]\n|work_institutions = \n|alma_mater        = Yale University \n|doctoral_advisor  = [[Richard Foster Flint]] \n|doctoral_students = \n|known_for         = [[Permafrost]] studies \n|influences        = \n|influenced        = \n|prizes            = [[Swedish Society for Anthropology and Geography#Recipients of the Vega Medal.5B4.5D|Vega Medal]] <small>(1997)</small>\n|religion          = \n|footnotes         = \n|signature         =\n}}\n\n'''Albert Lincoln \"Link\" Washburn''' (1911\u20132007) was an American [[geomorphology|geomorphologist]] studying [[permafrost]]. Washburn was a proficient skier participating in the [[1936 Winter Olympics]]. Much of his work on permafrost was done in the [[Northern Canada|Canadian arctic]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pubs.aina.ucalgary.ca/arctic/Arctic60-2-212.pdf |title=Albert Lincoln Washburn (1911\u20132007) |website=pubs.aina.ucalgary.ca}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links==\n* {{SR/Olympics profile|wa/link-washburn-1|Link Washburn}}\n* {{IOC profile|albert-lincoln-washburn|Albert Lincoln Washburn}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Washburn, Albert Lincoln}}\n[[Category:Alpine skiers at the 1936 Winter Olympics]]\n[[Category:American geomorphologists]]\n[[Category:Quaternary geologists]]\n[[Category:1911 births]]\n[[Category:2007 deaths]]\n[[Category:American male alpine skiers]]\n[[Category:Olympic alpine skiers of the United States]]\n\n\n{{US-alpine-skiing-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Igrallert", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:added link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Albert_Lincoln_Washburn"}
{"title_page": "Eugen Gondi", "text_new": "'''Eugen Gondi''' (b. 1947, in [[Timi\u0219oara]]) is a Romanian-born jazz drummer. \n\nHe graduated from the Arts Middle School in his hometown.\n\nHe started his musical career by playing with the \"Paul Weiner Free Jazz\" trio.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.urban.ro/evenimente/calendar/romanian-jazz-collective-feat-eugen-gondi|title=ROMANIAN JAZZ COLLECTIVE feat Eugen Gondi|language=Romanian|accessdate=December 25, 2013}}</ref>\n\nHe has played with many famous Romanian jazz players, like [[Marius Popp]], [[Johnny R\u0103ducanu]], [[Garbis Dedeian]], [[Radu Goldi\u015f]], [[Pedro Negrescu]], [[Dan M\u00e2ndril\u0103]], [[Jan Jankeje]], [[Liviu Butoi]]. For a time, in 1974, he was the drummer of rock band [[Transsylvania Phoenix]].\n\nHe is a former member of [[Mircea Florian (musician)|Mircea Florian]]'s concept-band ''[[Ceata Melopoic\u0103]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jurnalul.ro/vechiul-site/old-site/suplimente/editie-de-colectie/dor-de-transilvania-25896.html|title=Dor de Transilvania|publisher=jurnalul.ro|language=Romanian|accessdate=December 25, 2013}}</ref>\n\nHe participated at several jazz festivals, such as the ones in [[Ploie\u015fti]], [[Sibiu]], [[San Sebasti\u00e1n]], [[Warsaw]], [[P\u0159erov]], and [[Ljubliana]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jazzcompas.com/2013/01/23/interviu-cu-jhsakjdha/?relatedposts_exclude=267|title=Gondi.|publisher=jazzcompass.com|language=Romanian|accessdate=December 25, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131227101823/http://jazzcompas.com/2013/01/23/interviu-cu-jhsakjdha/?relatedposts_exclude=267|archivedate=December 27, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAfter the [[Romanian Revolution of 1989]], he emigrated to [[the Netherlands]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://adevarul.ro/locale/timisoara/povestea-incredibila-bateristului-preferat-johnny-raducanu-ajuns-restaurator-muzeului-regal-olanda-spalat-wc-uri-1_50ad2eaa7c42d5a66390467a/index.html|title=Povestea incredibil\u0103 a bateristului preferat al lui Johnny R\u0103ducanu: a ajuns restaurator al Muzeului Regal din Olanda, dup\u0103 ce a sp\u0103lat WC-uri|publisher=Adevarul.ro|language=Romanian|accessdate=December 25, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n==External links==\n* [http://www.discogs.com/artist/Eugen+Gondi Eugen Gondi at Discogs]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20131227101823/http://jazzcompas.com/2013/01/23/interviu-cu-jhsakjdha/?relatedposts_exclude=267 Interview with Eugen Gondi Part I] {{in lang|ro}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20131227104158/http://jazzcompas.com/2013/02/01/interviu-cu-eugen-gondi-partea-ii-a/ Interview with Eugen Gondi Part II] {{in lang|ro}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gondi, Eugen}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Timi\u0219oara]]\n[[Category:Romanian percussionists]]\n[[Category:Romanian drummers]]\n[[Category:Romanian emigrants to the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Romanian jazz musicians]]\n\n{{jazz-musician-stub}}\n{{Romania-musician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Eugen Gondi''' (b. 1947, in [[Timi\u015foara]]) is a Romanian-born jazz drummer. \n\nHe graduated from the Arts Middle School in his hometown.\n\nHe started his musical career by playing with the \"Paul Weiner Free Jazz\" trio.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.urban.ro/evenimente/calendar/romanian-jazz-collective-feat-eugen-gondi|title=ROMANIAN JAZZ COLLECTIVE feat Eugen Gondi|language=Romanian|accessdate=December 25, 2013}}</ref>\n\nHe has played with many famous Romanian jazz players, like [[Marius Popp]], [[Johnny R\u0103ducanu]], [[Garbis Dedeian]], [[Radu Goldi\u015f]], [[Pedro Negrescu]], [[Dan M\u00e2ndril\u0103]], [[Jan Jankeje]], [[Liviu Butoi]]. For a time, in 1974, he was the drummer of rock band [[Transsylvania Phoenix]].\n\nHe is a former member of [[Mircea Florian (musician)|Mircea Florian]]'s concept-band ''[[Ceata Melopoic\u0103]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jurnalul.ro/vechiul-site/old-site/suplimente/editie-de-colectie/dor-de-transilvania-25896.html|title=Dor de Transilvania|publisher=jurnalul.ro|language=Romanian|accessdate=December 25, 2013}}</ref>\n\nHe participated at several jazz festivals, such as the ones in [[Ploie\u015fti]], [[Sibiu]], [[San Sebasti\u00e1n]], [[Warsaw]], [[P\u0159erov]], and [[Ljubliana]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jazzcompas.com/2013/01/23/interviu-cu-jhsakjdha/?relatedposts_exclude=267|title=Gondi.|publisher=jazzcompass.com|language=Romanian|accessdate=December 25, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131227101823/http://jazzcompas.com/2013/01/23/interviu-cu-jhsakjdha/?relatedposts_exclude=267|archivedate=December 27, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAfter the [[Romanian Revolution of 1989]], he emigrated to [[the Netherlands]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://adevarul.ro/locale/timisoara/povestea-incredibila-bateristului-preferat-johnny-raducanu-ajuns-restaurator-muzeului-regal-olanda-spalat-wc-uri-1_50ad2eaa7c42d5a66390467a/index.html|title=Povestea incredibil\u0103 a bateristului preferat al lui Johnny R\u0103ducanu: a ajuns restaurator al Muzeului Regal din Olanda, dup\u0103 ce a sp\u0103lat WC-uri|publisher=Adevarul.ro|language=Romanian|accessdate=December 25, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n==External links==\n* [http://www.discogs.com/artist/Eugen+Gondi Eugen Gondi at Discogs]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20131227101823/http://jazzcompas.com/2013/01/23/interviu-cu-jhsakjdha/?relatedposts_exclude=267 Interview with Eugen Gondi Part I] {{in lang|ro}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20131227104158/http://jazzcompas.com/2013/02/01/interviu-cu-eugen-gondi-partea-ii-a/ Interview with Eugen Gondi Part II] {{in lang|ro}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gondi, Eugen}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Timi\u0219oara]]\n[[Category:Romanian percussionists]]\n[[Category:Romanian drummers]]\n[[Category:Romanian emigrants to the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Romanian jazz musicians]]\n\n{{jazz-musician-stub}}\n{{Romania-musician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Wbm1058", "label": "safe", "comment": "Timi\u0219oara(viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eugen_Gondi"}
{"title_page": "R-Line (Norfolk Southern)", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=January 2017}}\n\nThe '''R-Line''' is a secondary main railway line running between [[Charlotte, North Carolina]], and [[Augusta, Georgia]], United States. The line is operated by [[Norfolk Southern Railway|Norfolk Southern (NS)]] as part of the railway's '''Piedmont Division'''. The R-Line originally operated by the former [[Charlotte, Columbia and Augusta Railroad]] before being merged in 1878 with the [[Richmond and Danville Railroad|Richmond and Danville]] which merged with the [[Southern Railway (U.S.)|Southern]] in 1894.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://railga.com/charlcol.html |title=Charlotte, Columbia & Augusta Railroad  |website=Railga.com |date= |accessdate=December 18, 2016}}</ref> Today it was now operated by NS.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.r-line-video.com/viewitem.php?productid=19 |title=Trains (and Some Trolleys)  |website=Railroad DVD and Blu-ray by R-Line Video |date= |accessdate=December 18, 2016}}</ref>\n\nTrains on the R-Line are mostly [[Glossary of North American railway terms#M|manifest]], [[grain]], [[coal]], [[scrap]], chemicals, and locals.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://railfandepot.com/product/norfolk-southerns-r-line-trains-trolleys |title=Trains (and Some Trolleys)  |website=Railfan Depot |date= |accessdate=December 18, 2016}}</ref> Manifests to and from [[Linwood Yard]] use the line on a daily basis.  Grain trains that use the R-Line are bound to and from [[Asheville, North Carolina]].\n\nCrew changes for Linwood Yard and Asheville through trains occur in [[Salisbury, North Carolina]].\n\nAll trains are required to be given track authorities from the Columbia Dispatcher.\n\nAll southbound trains on the R-Line make connections to Savannah and Atlanta via the D-Line from Augusta, GA.\n\n== History ==\n\nThe Norfolk Southern R-Line.. Originally built and owned by the Charlotte and South Carolina Railway in 1852 was acquired by the Southern Railway in 1892. Trains continue to operate on the R-Line today and are all operated by the Norfolk Southern Railway. Trains Historically ran from Augusta, GA to Downtown Charlotte direct without using the Present day Norfolk Southern Charlotte District. In 1950 The Berryhill Cutoff was created connecting the R-line in South Charlotte to the Piedmont Division Via. Charlotte Junction keeping traffic of the South Charlotte to Uptown Charlotte Segment. Locals ran on the short segment of track until 1990. By then the segment of track was designated as the 'Old R Line' by the FRA.\n\nIn the Late 90's/early 2000s a temporary streetcar operation was done on the very so right of way from [[Atherton Mill station]] in South End to Scaleybark Road in South Charlotte while roadbed was being rebuilt for operations from Atherton Mill to uptown Charlotte for future trolley operations. All operations on the old R Line ceased in 2002 once the new trolley main opened.\n\nAll old tracks and signaling were later removed and rebuilt on the right of way between 2005-2007 to make way for what is the present day [[Lynx Blue Line]]. Some of the Lynx right of way had to be re-accommodated next to the active portions of the NS R-line.\n\nAll Trains On The R-line Must Stop In NS Columbia Yard.\n\n== Locals ==\n'''P32''' (Rock Hill, SC To Catawba, SC Turn)\n\n'''P36''' (Rock Hill, SC To Chester, SC Turn)\n\n'''P38''' (Pineville, NC To Rock Hill, SC Turn)\n\n'''P39''' (Pineville, NC To Rock Hill, SC)\n\n'''P40''' (Pineville, NC To Rock Hill, SC)\n\n'''P53''' (Charlotte, NC To Pineville, NC Turn)\n\n'''P75''' (Columbia, SC To Johnston, SC Turn)\n\n'''P77''' (Columbia, SC To Edmund, SC Turn)\n\n'''P83''' (Rock Hill, SC To Chester, SC Turn)\n\n'''P85''' (Columbia, SC To Union, SC Turn)\n\n== Manifest ==\n'''#191''' (Southbound) (Linwood, NC To Macon, GA) Works Yards: Augusta, Ga, Savannah, GA, Charleston, SC, Columbia, SC, Rock Hill, SC, and Charlotte, NC\n\n'''#192''' (Northbound) (Macon, GA To Linwood, NC) Works Yards: Charlotte, NC, Rock Hill, SC, Columbia, SC, Charleston, SC, Savannah, GA and Augusta, Ga.\n\n== Intermodal  ==\n'''#24Q''' (Northbound) (Charleston, SC To Elizabeth, NJ) Baretables\nSundays Only\n\n== Coal ==\n'''#786''' (Southbund) (Loudon, Tennessee To Wateree, South Carolina)\n\n'''#787'''  (Northbound) (Wateree, South Carolina To Loudon, Tennessee)\n\n== Grain == \nThere Are Many Other Grain Trains But These Are The 4 Main Ones.\n\n'''#50D''' (Southbound) (Unknown To Columbia, SC)\n\n'''#51D''' (Northbound) (Columbia, SC To Unknown)\n\n'''#51G''' (Northbound) (Baldwin, GA To Muncie, IN) \n\n'''#52G''' (Southbound) (Muncie, IN To Baldwin, GA)\n\n'''#51W''' (Northbound) (Columbia, SC To Dwight, IL)\n\n'''#50W''' (Southbound) (Dwight, IL To Columbia, SC)\n\n== Ethanol ==\n'''#64H''' Ethanol Loads (Southbound) (Chicago, IL CN To Westover, GA)\n\n'''#65H''' Ethanol Empties (Northbound) (Westover, GA To Chicago, IL CN)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Norfolk Southern Railway lines]]\n[[Category:Rail infrastructure in North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Rail infrastructure in South Carolina]]\n[[Category:Rail infrastructure in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=January 2017}}\n\nThe '''R-Line''' is a secondary main railway line running between [[Charlotte, North Carolina]], and [[Augusta, Georgia]], United States. The line is operated by [[Norfolk Southern Railway|Norfolk Southern (NS)]] as part of the railway's '''Piedmont Division'''. The R-Line originally operated by the former [[Charlotte, Columbia and Augusta Railroad]] before being merged in 1878 with the [[Richmond and Danville Railroad|Richmond and Danville]] which merged with the [[Southern Railway (U.S.)|Southern]] in 1894.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://railga.com/charlcol.html |title=Charlotte, Columbia & Augusta Railroad  |website=Railga.com |date= |accessdate=December 18, 2016}}</ref> Today it was now operated by NS.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.r-line-video.com/viewitem.php?productid=19 |title=Trains (and Some Trolleys)  |website=Railroad DVD and Blu-ray by R-Line Video |date= |accessdate=December 18, 2016}}</ref>\n\nTrains on the R-Line are mostly [[Glossary of North American railway terms#M|manifest]], [[grain]], [[coal]], [[scrap]], chemicals, and locals.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://railfandepot.com/product/norfolk-southerns-r-line-trains-trolleys |title=Trains (and Some Trolleys)  |website=Railfan Depot |date= |accessdate=December 18, 2016}}</ref> Manifests to and from [[Linwood Yard]] use the line on a daily basis.  Grain trains that use the R-Line are bound to and from [[Asheville, North Carolina]].\n\nCrew changes for Linwood Yard and Asheville through trains occur in [[Salisbury, North Carolina]].\n\nAll trains are required to be given track authorities from the Columbia Dispatcher.\n\nAll southbound trains on the R-Line make connections to Savannah and Atlanta via the D-Line from Augusta, GA.\n\n== History ==\n\nThe Norfolk Southern R-Line.. Originally built and owned by the Charlotte and South Carolina Railway in 1852 was acquired by the Southern Railway in 1892. Trains continue to operate on the R-Line today and are all operated by the Norfolk Southern Railway. Trains Historically ran from Augusta, GA to Downtown Charlotte direct without using the Present day Norfolk Southern Charlotte District. In 1950 The Berryhill Cutoff was created connecting the R-line in South Charlotte to the Piedmont Division Via. Charlotte Junction keeping traffic of the South Charlotte to Uptown Charlotte Segment. Locals ran on the short segment of track until 1990. By then the segment of track was designated as the 'Old R Line' by the FRA.\n\nIn the Late 90's/early 2000's a temporary streetcar operation was done on the very so right of way from [[Atherton Mill station]] in South End to Scaleybark Road in South Charlotte while roadbed was being rebuilt for operations from Atherton Mill to uptown Charlotte for future trolley operations. All operations on the old R Line ceased in 2002 once the new trolley main opened.\n\nAll old tracks and signaling were later removed and rebuilt on the right of way between 2005-2007 to make way for what is the present day [[Lynx Blue Line]]. Some of the Lynx right of way had to be re-accommodated next to the active portions of the NS R-line.\n\nAll Trains On The R-line Must Stop In NS Columbia Yard.\n\n== Locals ==\n'''P32''' (Rock Hill, SC To Catawba, SC Turn)\n\n'''P36''' (Rock Hill, SC To Chester, SC Turn)\n\n'''P38''' (Pineville, NC To Rock Hill, SC Turn)\n\n'''P39''' (Pineville, NC To Rock Hill, SC)\n\n'''P40''' (Pineville, NC To Rock Hill, SC)\n\n'''P53''' (Charlotte, NC To Pineville, NC Turn)\n\n'''P75''' (Columbia, SC To Johnston, SC Turn)\n\n'''P77''' (Columbia, SC To Edmund, SC Turn)\n\n'''P83''' (Rock Hill, SC To Chester, SC Turn)\n\n'''P85''' (Columbia, SC To Union, SC Turn)\n\n== Manifest ==\n'''#191''' (Southbound) (Linwood, NC To Macon, GA) Works Yards: Augusta, Ga, Savannah, GA, Charleston, SC, Columbia, SC, Rock Hill, SC, and Charlotte, NC\n\n'''#192''' (Northbound) (Macon, GA To Linwood, NC) Works Yards: Charlotte, NC, Rock Hill, SC, Columbia, SC, Charleston, SC, Savannah, GA and Augusta, Ga.\n\n== Intermodal  ==\n'''#24Q''' (Northbound) (Charleston, SC To Elizabeth, NJ) Baretables\nSundays Only\n\n== Coal ==\n'''#786''' (Southbund) (Loudon, Tennessee To Wateree, South Carolina)\n\n'''#787'''  (Northbound) (Wateree, South Carolina To Loudon, Tennessee)\n\n== Grain == \nThere Are Many Other Grain Trains But These Are The 4 Main Ones.\n\n'''#50D''' (Southbound) (Unknown To Columbia, SC)\n\n'''#51D''' (Northbound) (Columbia, SC To Unknown)\n\n'''#51G''' (Northbound) (Baldwin, GA To Muncie, IN) \n\n'''#52G''' (Southbound) (Muncie, IN To Baldwin, GA)\n\n'''#51W''' (Northbound) (Columbia, SC To Dwight, IL)\n\n'''#50W''' (Southbound) (Dwight, IL To Columbia, SC)\n\n== Ethanol ==\n'''#64H''' Ethanol Loads (Southbound) (Chicago, IL CN To Westover, GA)\n\n'''#65H''' Ethanol Empties (Northbound) (Westover, GA To Chicago, IL CN)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Norfolk Southern Railway lines]]\n[[Category:Rail infrastructure in North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Rail infrastructure in South Carolina]]\n[[Category:Rail infrastructure in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/R-Line_(Norfolk_Southern)"}
{"title_page": "Lines & Circles", "text_new": "{{primary sources|date=March 2016}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Lines & Circles\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[O-Town]]\n| cover      = Linesandcirclesotown.jpg\n| border     = yes\n| alt        =\n| released   = August 25, 2014\n| recorded   = 2011-2014\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Pop music|Pop]], [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n| length     = 35:16\n| label      = All About the Melody\n| producer   = Phillip LaRue, Samuel Adams, Mark Suhonen, [[Ryan Tedder]], Chizzy Stephens III, Sam Gray, Gary Vaughan, Steve White, Patrik Patrikios, Phil Shaouy\n| prev_title = [[O2 (O-Town album)|O2]]\n| prev_year  = 2002\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Lines & Circles\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = Skydive\n | single1date = July 27, 2014\n | single2     = Chasin' After You\n | single2date = September 29, 2014\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Lines & Circles''''' is the third studio album released by American [[boy band]] [[O-Town]], and the first to be released by the band since their reunion as a four-piece in 2011. The album was recorded over the course of three years, with a number of writers and producers, including [[Ryan Tedder]].<ref>http://www.otownofficial.com/</ref>\n\nThe album was initially due for release on August 3, 2014, but was delayed by three weeks to August 25, due to final touches being made to the production. The band released a mock video on [[YouTube]] which claimed the reason for the delay was due to band member Erik Michael Estrada changing the cover art to resemble the cover for the single \"[[Anaconda (Nicki Minaj song)|Anaconda]]\" by [[Nicki Minaj]].<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BUb6Gnf_0C0</ref> The lead single from the album, \"Skydive\", was released on July 27, 2014<ref name=\"Apple Music\">https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/skydive-single/882810911</ref>, after being pushed back from the initial release date of June 19, 2014.<ref name=\"youtube.com\">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=12aX6fKuDfs</ref>\n\n==Background==\nThe band officially reformed as a four-piece in 2011, without original band member [[Ashley Parker Angel]]. Angel declined a return to the group, despite being approached by more than two of the band members. The band released an official statement which said that they \"understood Ashley's decision\", and \"will continue as a band without his input\", and \"wish him all of the best in his future ventures\". The band later announced the album's release date to be August 4, 2014 in a video via their official [[YouTube]] account.<ref name=\"youtube.com\"/>\n\n==Songwriters==\nThe band worked with a number of songwriters and producers on the album, which was recorded over the space of three years. High-profile contributors include country singer-songwriter [[Phillip LaRue]], who contributed to \"Chasin' After You\" and \"Rewind\", and [[OneRepublic]] lead singer [[Ryan Tedder]], who co-wrote and co-produced \"I Won't Lose\". Band member Jacob Underwood co-wrote five of the songs on the album, while Erik Michael Estrada co-wrote title track \"Lines and Circles\". It is notable that band member Dan Miller is the only band member not to receive a writing credit on the album.\n\nThe album is notable for covering a number of different genres. \"Chasin' After You\" is a [[Michael Jackson]]-esque dancefloor filler with soft, harmonic high-range melodies on the hook. \"Skydive\" is a soaring boy band ballad with pianos and drums aplenty. \"Rewind\" is an electro-rock mash up with a '[[We Will Rock You]]'-esque beat accompanied perfectly by an electro-hopping bassline. \"Playing With Fire\" has a [[One Direction]] reminiscent guitar-lead intro, but soon leaps into a R&B fusion chorus with keyboards and harmonies aplenty. \"I Won't Lose\" is an acoustically-lead ballad that falls somewhere in the boundary between [[Take That]] and [[The Script]]. \"Right Kind of Wrong\" has possibly the strongest influences of R&B on the record, although soon crosses the threshold into pop-rap with a rap breakdown. \"Buried Alive\" is a reggae-tinged acoustic jive. \"Got to Go\" is a classic early 2000s boy band ballad. \"Sometimes Love Just Ain't Enough\" is a laid-back melodic ballad, drawing comparisons to early material from the [[Backstreet Boys]]. \"Lines and Circles\" is a heavy instrumentally-lead electro-pop ballad.\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed       = no\n| extra_column    = Producer(s)\n| title1   = Chasin' After You\n| writer1  = [[Phillip LaRue]] \u2022 Jacob Underwood \u2022 Mark Suhonen\n| extra1   = Suhonen \u2022 Jacob Underwood\n| length1  = 3:22\n| title2   = Skydive\n| writer2  = Marcel Wildly \u2022 Samuel Adams\n| extra2   = Suhonen \u2022 Jacob Underwood \u2022 Adams \n| length2  = 3:39\n| title3   = Rewind\n| writer3  = LaRue \u2022 Jacob Underwood \u2022 Suhonen\n| extra3   = Suhonen \u2022 Jacob Underwood\n| length3  = 4:32\n| title4   = Playing With Fire\n| writer4  = Jacob Underwood \u2022 Jonathon Lucas \u2022 Tyler Cain \n| extra4   = Suhonen \u2022 Jacob Underwood\n| length4  = 3:14\n| title5   = I Won't Lose\n| writer5  = Jarell Perry \u2022 Jack Tremaine Jones \u2022 Chizzy Stephens III \u2022 [[Ryan Tedder]]\n| extra5   = Stephens III \u2022 Timothy Zimnoch \u2022 Tedder \n| length5  = 3:51\n| title6   = Right Kind of Wrong\n| writer6  = Jacob Underwood \u2022 Stephens III \u2022 Trevor Penick \u2022 Erik Michael Estrada \u2022 Carlos Battey\n| extra6   = Stephens III \u2022 Zimnoch\n| length6  = 3:16\n| title7   = Buried Alive\n| writer7  = Sam Gray \u2022 Joe Killington\n| extra7   = Gray \u2022 Eddie Galan\n| length7  = 3:30\n| title8   = Got to Go\n| writer8  = Gray \u2022 Killington\n| extra8   = Gray \u2022 Galan \u2022 Patrik Patrikios \u2022 Steve White \u2022 Gary Vaughan \n| length8  = 4:07\n| title9   = Sometimes Love Just Ain't Enough\n| writer9  = Gray \u2022 Killington\n| extra9   = Gray \u2022 Galan \u2022 Stephens III\n| length9  = 4:24\n| title10  = Lines & Circles\n| writer10 = Erik Michael Estrada \u2022 Phil Shaouy\n| extra10  = Shaouy\n| length10 = 3:30\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{O-Town}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lines and Circles}}\n[[Category:2014 albums]]\n[[Category:O-Town albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{primary sources|date=March 2016}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Lines & Circles\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[O-Town]]\n| cover      = Linesandcirclesotown.jpg\n| border     = yes\n| alt        =\n| released   = August 25, 2014\n| recorded   = 2011-2014\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Pop music|Pop]], [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n| length     = 35:16\n| label      = All About the Melody\n| producer   = Phillip LaRue, Samuel Adams, Mark Suhonen, [[Ryan Tedder]], Chizzy Stephens III, Sam Gray, Gary Vaughan, Steve White, Patrik Patrikios, Phil Shaouy\n| prev_title = [[O2 (O-Town album)|O2]]\n| prev_year  = 2002\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Lines & Circles\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = Skydive\n | single1date = July 27, 2014\n | single2     = Chasin' After You\n | single2date = September 29, 2014\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Lines & Circles''''' is the third studio album released by American [[boy band]] [[O-Town]], and the first to be released by the band since their reunion as a four-piece in 2011. The album was recorded over the course of three years, with a number of writers and producers, including [[Ryan Tedder]].<ref>http://www.otownofficial.com/</ref>\n\nThe album was initially due for release on August 3, 2014, but was delayed by three weeks to August 25, due to final touches being made to the production. The band released a mock video on [[YouTube]] which claimed the reason for the delay was due to band member Erik Michael Estrada changing the cover art to resemble the cover for the single \"[[Anaconda (Nicki Minaj song)|Anaconda]]\" by [[Nicki Minaj]].<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BUb6Gnf_0C0</ref> The lead single from the album, \"Skydive\", was released on July 27, 2014<ref name=\"Apple Music\">https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/skydive-single/882810911</ref>, after being pushed back from the initial release date of June 19, 2014.<ref name=\"youtube.com\">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=12aX6fKuDfs</ref>\n\n==Background==\nThe band officially reformed as a four-piece in 2011, without original band member [[Ashley Parker Angel]]. Angel declined a return to the group, despite being approached by more than two of the band members. The band released an official statement which said that they \"understood Ashley's decision\", and \"will continue as a band without his input\", and \"wish him all of the best in his future ventures\". The band later announced the album's release date to be August 4, 2014 in a video via their official [[YouTube]] account.<ref name=\"youtube.com\"/>\n\n==Songwriters==\nThe band worked with a number of songwriters and producers on the album, which was recorded over the space of three years. High-profile contributors include country singer-songwriter [[Phillip LaRue]], who contributed to \"Chasin' After You\" and \"Rewind\", and [[OneRepublic]] lead singer [[Ryan Tedder]], who co-wrote and co-produced \"I Won't Lose\". Band member Jacob Underwood co-wrote five of the songs on the album, while Erik Michael Estrada co-wrote title track \"Lines and Circles\". It is notable that band member Dan Miller is the only band member not to receive a writing credit on the album.\n\nThe album is notable for covering a number of different genres. \"Chasin' After You\" is a [[Michael Jackson]]-esque dancefloor filler with soft, harmonic high-range melodies on the hook. \"Skydive\" is a soaring boy band ballad with pianos and drums aplenty. \"Rewind\" is an electro-rock mash up with a '[[We Will Rock You]]'-esque beat accompanied perfectly by an electro-hopping bassline. \"Playing With Fire\" has a [[One Direction]] reminiscent guitar-lead intro, but soon leaps into a R&B fusion chorus with keyboards and harmonies aplenty. \"I Won't Lose\" is an acoustically-lead ballad that falls somewhere in the boundary between [[Take That]] and [[The Script]]. \"Right Kind of Wrong\" has possibly the strongest influences of R&B on the record, although soon crosses the threshold into pop-rap with a rap breakdown. \"Buried Alive\" is a reggae-tinged acoustic jive. \"Got to Go\" is a classic early 2000's boy band ballad. \"Sometimes Love Just Ain't Enough\" is a laid-back melodic ballad, drawing comparisons to early material from the [[Backstreet Boys]]. \"Lines and Circles\" is a heavy instrumentally-lead electro-pop ballad.\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed       = no\n| extra_column    = Producer(s)\n| title1   = Chasin' After You\n| writer1  = [[Phillip LaRue]] \u2022 Jacob Underwood \u2022 Mark Suhonen\n| extra1   = Suhonen \u2022 Jacob Underwood\n| length1  = 3:22\n| title2   = Skydive\n| writer2  = Marcel Wildly \u2022 Samuel Adams\n| extra2   = Suhonen \u2022 Jacob Underwood \u2022 Adams \n| length2  = 3:39\n| title3   = Rewind\n| writer3  = LaRue \u2022 Jacob Underwood \u2022 Suhonen\n| extra3   = Suhonen \u2022 Jacob Underwood\n| length3  = 4:32\n| title4   = Playing With Fire\n| writer4  = Jacob Underwood \u2022 Jonathon Lucas \u2022 Tyler Cain \n| extra4   = Suhonen \u2022 Jacob Underwood\n| length4  = 3:14\n| title5   = I Won't Lose\n| writer5  = Jarell Perry \u2022 Jack Tremaine Jones \u2022 Chizzy Stephens III \u2022 [[Ryan Tedder]]\n| extra5   = Stephens III \u2022 Timothy Zimnoch \u2022 Tedder \n| length5  = 3:51\n| title6   = Right Kind of Wrong\n| writer6  = Jacob Underwood \u2022 Stephens III \u2022 Trevor Penick \u2022 Erik Michael Estrada \u2022 Carlos Battey\n| extra6   = Stephens III \u2022 Zimnoch\n| length6  = 3:16\n| title7   = Buried Alive\n| writer7  = Sam Gray \u2022 Joe Killington\n| extra7   = Gray \u2022 Eddie Galan\n| length7  = 3:30\n|