er|Worcester}}\n ! {{vert header|Unknown}}\n ! style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888\" |Source\n|}\n\n== Government response ==\nCiting the rapid increase in cases, Governor Charlie Baker declared a [[state of emergency]] for Massachusetts on March 10.<ref>{{Cite news | url = https://www.wcvb.com/article/governor-charlie-baker-declares-state-of-emergency-coronavirus-3-10-2020/31356404 | title = Gov. Baker declares state of emergency as Mass. coronavirus cases more than double | date = March 10, 2020 | work = WCVB | access-date = March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | last = Locke | first = Kaitlyn | url = https://www.wgbh.org/news/local-news/2020/03/10/baker-declares-state-of-emergency-92-total-coronavirus-cases-in-massachusetts | title = Baker Declares State Of Emergency; 92 Total Coronavirus Cases in Massachusetts | date = March 10, 2020 | work = WGBH News | access-date = March 13, 2020}}</ref> During a press conference at 11:00 on March 14, 2020, Governor Baker established an emergency command center, with multiple state departments working with contact with one another, Baker also promised an expansion of statewide lab testing. <!-- https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/03/14/metro/baker-sets-up-virus-command-center/ -->\n\nOn March 15, Governor Baker banned all public gatherings of over 25 people, closed all K-12 public schools from March 17 through April 7, and banned on-site service at bars and restaurants for the same period.<ref>{{cite news | title = Gov. Baker bans gatherings of over 25 people, orders school closure, restaurants take-out only | url = https://www.wcvb.com/article/gov-charlie-baker-massachusetts-covid-19-coronavirus-update-march-15-2020/31647097 | access-date = March 17, 2020 | work = WCVB | date = March 16, 2020}}</ref> On March 25, Governor Baker ordered all schools and childcare services to be closed through May 4, extending the original length by 3 weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mass.gov/news/baker-polito-administration-announces-extension-of-school-and-non-emergency-child-care-program|title=Baker-Polito Administration Announces Extension of School and Non-Emergency Child Care Program Closures and Steps to Ensure Housing Stability To Support COVID-19 Response|author=\nOffice of Governor Charlie Baker and Lt. Governor Karyn Polito|publisher=Mass.gov|date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 23, Governor Baker announced his stay-at-home advisory effective March 24 until April 7.<ref name=Feuer/>\n\n== Economic and social effects ==\nThe sudden surge of cases in Massachusetts during the week of March 9, led to many organizations ordering workers to work from home and closures of museums and libraries, leading to a noticeable decline of Boston's notorious rush hour traffic. In some cases, drive times for major highways during Boston's rush hour dropped by 30 to 50 percent.<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.boston.com/news/local-news/2020/03/11/boston-traffic-coronavirus | title = Coronavirus: Here's how much Boston's rush hour traffic has dropped &#124; Boston.com | website = Boston.com}}</ref> [[Panic buying]], especially since the week of March 11, led to shortages of various products, with many shoppers and long lines at grocery stores as early in the day as 7:00&nbsp;a.m.<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/03/13/nation/store-shelves-picked-clean-people-panic-buy-goods-local-supermarkets/ | title = Store shelves picked clean as people panic-buy goods at local supermarkets \u2013 The Boston Globe | website = [[The Boston Globe]] }}</ref> In response, some grocery retailers such as Stop & Shop adjusted their hours to allow employees more time to restock and to offer older and more vulnerable people a separate time where they can shop separately, but reminded shoppers to practice distancing. {{citation needed|date=March 2020}}<!-- nhttps://boston.cbslocal.com/2020/03/16/coronavirus-stop-and-shop-senior-hours/amp/?__twitter_impression=true -->\n\n=== School closures ===\nSchool closures began in early March, starting on March 9, when MIT announced it was moving to only-online classes for the remainder of the spring semester.<ref name=\"MIT-Update\" /> Also, on March 9, two elementary schools in the [[Plainville, Massachusetts|Plainville]] school district and one in [[Arlington, Massachusetts|Arlington]] were closed for the day due to tests being conducted on two parents and one child.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Cuoco | first = John | url = https://whdh.com/news/multiple-massachusetts-schools-closed-monday-as-coronavirus-cases-continue-to-rise/ | title = Multiple Massachusetts schools closed Monday as coronavirus cases continue to rise | date = March 9, 2020 | work = WHDH 7News | access-date = March 11, 2020}}</ref> School districts began closing on March 11. Within a week, many colleges and state school districts announced closures ranging from weeks to months in duration.<ref name=\"Williams-Update\" /><ref name=\"Williams-Colleges\" />\n\nWellesley and Framingham closed their public schools and libraries for two weeks on March 13.<ref>{{cite web | title = WPS Update 3/13/2020 | website = Wellesley Public Schools | date = March 13, 2020 | url = https://wellesleyps.org/blog/2020/03/13/wps-update-3-13-2020/ | access-date = March 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Town of Wellesley COVID-19 Update 3/13/2020 | website = Wellesley Public Schools | date = March 13, 2020 | url = https://wellesleyps.org/blog/2020/03/13/town-of-wellesley-covid-19-update-3-13-2020/ | access-date = March 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Framingham Library, Callahan Center, Loring Arena, and Public Schools to Close for a Minimum of Two Weeks Starting Friday, March 13 | website = Framingham, MA | date = March 13, 2020 | url = https://www.framinghamma.gov/CivicAlerts.aspx?AID=2023 | access-date = March 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release | title = Framingham Library, Callahan Center, Loring Arena, and Public Schools to Close for a Minimum of Two Weeks Starting Friday, March 13 | website = Framingham, MA | date = March 13, 2020 | url = https://www.framinghamma.gov/DocumentCenter/View/37162/Press-Release---COVID-19-Update-031320204265 | access-date = March 15, 2020}}</ref> Also on March 13, Boston announced that its public schools close for six weeks from Tuesday, March 17 through April 26.<ref>{{cite web | title = Boston Public Schools to close Tuesday, with plans to reopen April 27 | website = [[The Boston Globe]] | date = March 13, 2020 | url = https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/03/13/nation/mayor-walsh-address-coronavirus-outbreak-friday-evening/ | access-date = March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 15, Governor Baker ordered all schools in Massachusetts closed for three weeks from March 17 through April 7.<ref name=\"Becker\" /> On March 25, Governor Baker extended the order with schools to open no sooner than May 4.<ref>{{cite news |title=Baker: schools to open no sooner than May 4th |url=https://www.westernmassnews.com/news/baker-schools-to-open-no-sooner-than-may/article_dfa2979c-6ed0-11ea-8d2f-9f9402f5677e.html |accessdate=25 March 2020 |publisher=www.westernmassnews.com |date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Sports ===\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports}}\nMost of state's sports teams were affected. Several leagues began postponing or suspending their seasons starting March 12. [[Major League Baseball]] canceled the remainder of spring training on that date, and on March 16, they announced that the season would be postponed indefinitely, after the recommendations from the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]] to restrict events of more than 50 people for the next eight weeks, affecting the [[2020 Boston Red Sox season|Boston Red Sox]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.mlb.com/news/opening-of-regular-season-to-be-pushed-back | title = Opening of regular season to be pushed back | first = Mark | last = Feinsand | website = [[MLB.com]] | date = March 16, 2020 | access-date = March 16, 2020}}</ref> Also on March 12, the [[National Basketball Association]] announced the season would be suspended for 30 days, affecting the [[2019\u201320 Boston Celtics season|Boston Celtics]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28893331/nba-owners-seeking-30-day-reevaluation-suspension-games | title = Silver: NBA hiatus likely to last 'at least' 30 days | date = March 12, 2020 | website = ESPN.com | access-date = March 13, 2020}}</ref> Boston Celtics player [[Marcus Smart]] announced on March 18 that he had tested positive for COVID-19, having been tested five days prior.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wcvb.com/article/boston-celtics-player-tests-positive-for-coronavirus-team-confirms/31792637|title=Celtics' Marcus Smart tests positive for coronavirus|date=2020-03-20|website=WCVB|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref> In the [[National Hockey League]], the season was suspended for an indefinite amount of time, affecting the [[2019\u201320 Boston Bruins season|Boston Bruins]].<ref>[https://www.nhl.com/news/nhl-coronavirus-status/c-316155530 NHL statement on coronavirus] NHL, March 12, 2020</ref>\n\nIn college sports, the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] canceled all winter and spring tournaments, most notably the [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] [[2020 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|men]]'s and [[2020 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|women]]'s basketball tournaments, affecting colleges and universities statewide.<ref>[https://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships NCAA cancels remaining winter and spring championships] NCAA, March 12, 2020</ref> On March 16, the [[National Junior College Athletic Association]] also canceled the remainder of the winter seasons as well as the spring seasons.<ref>[https://www.mlive.com/sports/2020/03/njcaa-cancels-spring-sports-basketball-nationals-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html NJCAA cancels spring sports, basketball nationals amid coronavirus outbreak] MLive.com, March 16, 2020</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|COVID-19 pandemic in Massachusetts}}\n* [https://www.mass.gov/resource/information-on-the-outbreak-of-coronavirus-disease-2019-covid-19 Coronavirus information] from the [[Massachusetts Department of Public Health]]\n* {{cite web | title=COVID-19 Information and Resources | website=[[Massachusetts Department of Elementary and Secondary Education]] | url=http://www.doe.mass.edu/sfs/emergencyplan/covid19.html }}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Coronavirus disease 2019|Medicine|Pandemic|United States|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by state|Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:2020 in Massachusetts|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:February 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Health in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:January 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "name_user": "Okami*", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Massachusetts"}
{"title_page": "Chapel Field Christian Schools", "text_new": "{{Infobox School|name=Chapel Field Christian Schools|image=|established=1986|type=Private Christian School|students=\u2248 300|colors=Blue and Gold|mascot=Lion|address=211 Fleury Road|city=[[Pine Bush, New York|Pine Bush]]|state=[[New York (state)|New York]]|zipcode=12566|website={{url|chapelfield.org}}|logo=Chapelfield-designer-logo-navy.png|grades=Pre K - 12|campus_size=100 acres}}\n\n'''Chapel Field Christian Schools''' is a Pre K \u2013 12 [[Christian school]] located in [[Pine Bush, New York]]. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hvmag.com/Hudson-Valley-Magazine/Hudson-Valley-Resources/Education/|title=Hudson Valley Education|website=www.hvmag.com|language=en|access-date=2018-12-02}}</ref> The school was founded in 1986 by William and Kathleen Spanjer.<ref name=\"official-site\">{{cite web|url=http://www.chapelfield.org/about|title=Chapel Field- About|website=www.chapelfield.org|publisher=Chapel Field Christian Schools}}</ref> \n\n==History==\nIn 1979, the Spanjers founded Affirmative Evangelism Fellowship, a ministry devoted to Christian outreach.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Obstacle Course: The Long Road to Discipleship|last=Spanjer III|first=William H|publisher=Mindstir Media|year=2018|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> The ministry developed into a Christian high school in 1986.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aefministries.org/about-us|title=About Us \u2014 AEF - Affirmative Evangelism Fellowship, Inc.|website=AEF  -  Affirmative Evangelism Fellowship, Inc.|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-14}}</ref> Despite its humble beginnings, the school's reputation began to grow as did its numbers. In the early 2000s Chapel Field began developing a middle school program and in 2005 plans began for an elementary school building. In 2007, Chapel Field Elementary School began its first full school year. In 2013, the school rolled out its first official Pre K program, making it a Pre K through 12th grade school.\n\nIn the late 2000s the school established its international program. As of 2019, students from over 15 countries across 5 continents have attended the school. Chapel Field expanded its international initiative to include a boarding program in 2016. The boarding program is also available to domestic students.\n\nChapel Field is accredited by the National Association of Private Schools,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://napsschools.org/naps-schools-list/|title=NAPS Schools List|website=National Association of Private Schools|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-15}}</ref> and incorporated under the University of the State of New York. Chapel Field is a member of several athletic leagues and music associations. \n\nChapel Field Schools has been consistently ranked as one of the \"50 Best Christian Schools in America\" since The Best Schools (T.B.S.) began its annual rankings. <ref name=\"The Best Schools\">{{cite web|url=https://thebestschools.org/features/50-best-christian-high-schools-america/|title=50 Best Christian High Schools in America|website=www.thebestschools.org/features/50-best-christian-high-schools-america/|publisher=The Best Schools}}</ref>\n\n==Campus==\nChapel Field's 100 acre campus is located in the Hudson Valley region of New York State. Bridges span the Dwaarkill River, which runs through the center of the campus and is partially fed by the 2.5 acre lake on the southwestern end.{{cn|date=February 2019}} The school makes use of 4 buildings and 6 athletic fields.\n\n[[Image:chapelfield-school-letters-2019.png|250x250px|left|thumb|Chapel Field's School Letters|alt=]]\n\n==Athletics==\nChapel Field is part of the Orange County Interscholastic Athletic Association (OCIAA) in Class D.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://roia.ouboces.org/chapelfieldschedulepage.html|title=Chapel Field Schedules|website=roia.ouboces.org|access-date=2019-02-01}}</ref> It is one of only a few private schools in the Hudson Valley that compete athletically with public schools. Since it joined the OCIAA, Chapel Field has won 7 state championships. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nysphsaa.org/Sports/Softball/Past-Champions|title=NYSPHSAA > Sports > Softball > Past Champions|website=www.nysphsaa.org|access-date=2019-01-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.recordonline.com/sports31/99999999/champs---baseball|title=Champs - Baseball|website=recordonline.com|language=en|access-date=2017-11-15}}</ref> They participate in varsity, JV, and modified sports, including, Soccer (Boys/Girls); Basketball (Boys/Girls); Baseball (Boys); Softball (Girls); Track (Boys/Girls); Cross Country (Boys/Girls).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.maxpreps.com/high-schools/chapel-field-christian-(pine-bush,ny)/sports.htm|title=Chapel Field Christian Athletics and Sports Teams - Pine Bush, NY|website=www.maxpreps.com|access-date=2019-01-30}}</ref> Students may also potentially participate in other sports, depending on their local public school's policies. The school's mascot is a lion, which comes out of [[the Bible]], where [[Jesus Christ]] is referred to as the \u201cLion of Judah.\u201d\n\n'''<br />'''\n\n<br />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Coord|41|36|9|N|74|14|43|W|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Private high schools in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1986]]\n[[Category:Schools in Orange County, New York]]\n[[Category:Private middle schools in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Private elementary schools in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:1986 establishments in New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox School|name=Chapel Field Christian Schools|image=|established=1986|type=Private Christian School|students=\u2248 300|colors=Blue and Gold|mascot=Lion|address=211 Fleury Road|city=[[Pine Bush, New York|Pine Bush]]|state=[[New York (state)|New York]]|zipcode=12566|website={{url|chapelfield.org}}|logo=Chapelfield-designer-logo-navy.png|grades=Pre K - 12|campus_size=100 acres}}\n\n'''Chapel Field Christian Schools''' is a Pre K \u2013 12 [[Christian school]] located in [[Pine Bush, New York]]. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hvmag.com/Hudson-Valley-Magazine/Hudson-Valley-Resources/Education/|title=Hudson Valley Education|website=www.hvmag.com|language=en|access-date=2018-12-02}}</ref> The school was founded in 1986 by William and Kathleen Spanjer.<ref name=\"official-site\">{{cite web|url=http://www.chapelfield.org/about|title=Chapel Field- About|website=www.chapelfield.org|publisher=Chapel Field Christian Schools}}</ref> \n\n==History==\nIn 1979, the Spanjers founded Affirmative Evangelism Fellowship, a ministry devoted to Christian outreach.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Obstacle Course: The Long Road to Discipleship|last=Spanjer III|first=William H|publisher=Mindstir Media|year=2018|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> The ministry developed into a Christian high school in 1986.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aefministries.org/about-us|title=About Us \u2014 AEF - Affirmative Evangelism Fellowship, Inc.|website=AEF  -  Affirmative Evangelism Fellowship, Inc.|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-14}}</ref> Despite its humble beginnings, the school's reputation began to grow as did its numbers. In the early 2000's Chapel Field began developing a middle school program and in 2005 plans began for an elementary school building. In 2007, Chapel Field Elementary School began its first full school year. In 2013, the school rolled out its first official Pre K program, making it a Pre K through 12th grade school.\n\nIn the late 2000's the school established its international program. As of 2019, students from over 15 countries across 5 continents have attended the school. Chapel Field expanded its international initiative to include a boarding program in 2016. The boarding program is also available to domestic students.\n\nChapel Field is accredited by the National Association of Private Schools,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://napsschools.org/naps-schools-list/|title=NAPS Schools List|website=National Association of Private Schools|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-15}}</ref> and incorporated under the University of the State of New York. Chapel Field is a member of several athletic leagues and music associations. \n\nChapel Field Schools has been consistently ranked as one of the \"50 Best Christian Schools in America\" since The Best Schools (T.B.S.) began its annual rankings. <ref name=\"The Best Schools\">{{cite web|url=https://thebestschools.org/features/50-best-christian-high-schools-america/|title=50 Best Christian High Schools in America|website=www.thebestschools.org/features/50-best-christian-high-schools-america/|publisher=The Best Schools}}</ref>\n\n==Campus==\nChapel Field's 100 acre campus is located in the Hudson Valley region of New York State. Bridges span the Dwaarkill River, which runs through the center of the campus and is partially fed by the 2.5 acre lake on the southwestern end.{{cn|date=February 2019}} The school makes use of 4 buildings and 6 athletic fields.\n\n[[Image:chapelfield-school-letters-2019.png|250x250px|left|thumb|Chapel Field's School Letters|alt=]]\n\n==Athletics==\nChapel Field is part of the Orange County Interscholastic Athletic Association (OCIAA) in Class D.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://roia.ouboces.org/chapelfieldschedulepage.html|title=Chapel Field Schedules|website=roia.ouboces.org|access-date=2019-02-01}}</ref> It is one of only a few private schools in the Hudson Valley that compete athletically with public schools. Since it joined the OCIAA, Chapel Field has won 7 state championships. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nysphsaa.org/Sports/Softball/Past-Champions|title=NYSPHSAA > Sports > Softball > Past Champions|website=www.nysphsaa.org|access-date=2019-01-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.recordonline.com/sports31/99999999/champs---baseball|title=Champs - Baseball|website=recordonline.com|language=en|access-date=2017-11-15}}</ref> They participate in varsity, JV, and modified sports, including, Soccer (Boys/Girls); Basketball (Boys/Girls); Baseball (Boys); Softball (Girls); Track (Boys/Girls); Cross Country (Boys/Girls).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.maxpreps.com/high-schools/chapel-field-christian-(pine-bush,ny)/sports.htm|title=Chapel Field Christian Athletics and Sports Teams - Pine Bush, NY|website=www.maxpreps.com|access-date=2019-01-30}}</ref> Students may also potentially participate in other sports, depending on their local public school's policies. The school's mascot is a lion, which comes out of [[the Bible]], where [[Jesus Christ]] is referred to as the \u201cLion of Judah.\u201d\n\n'''<br />'''\n\n<br />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Coord|41|36|9|N|74|14|43|W|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Private high schools in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1986]]\n[[Category:Schools in Orange County, New York]]\n[[Category:Private middle schools in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Private elementary schools in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:1986 establishments in New York (state)]]\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chapel_Field_Christian_Schools"}
